{"title_page": "Kilinochchi", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See Template:Infobox Settlement for additional fields that may be available-->\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name                  = jaffna near\n|native_name            = \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0ba8\u0bca\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbf<br>\u0d9a\u0dd2\u0dbd\u0dd2\u0db1\u0ddc\u0da0\u0dca\u0da0\u0dd2\n|settlement_type        = [[Town]]\n|image_skyline          = Kilinochchi court of de-facto State Tamil Eelam.jpg\n|image_size             = 300px\n|image_caption          = Kilinochchi courthouse\n|pushpin_map            = Sri Lanka Northern Province\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = [[Sri Lanka]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Sri Lanka|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Northern Province (Sri Lanka)|Northern]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Sri Lanka|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Kilinochchi District|Kilinochchi]]\n|subdivision_type4 = [[Divisional Secretariats of Sri Lanka|DS Division]]\n|subdivision_name4 = Karachchi \n| population_as_of =\n| population_footnotes = \n| population_note = \n| population_total =\n|timezone = [[Time zone#UTC .2B 6.2C F|Sri Lanka Standard Time Zone]]\n|utc_offset = +5:30\n|timezone_DST = \n|utc_offset_DST = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|9|23|N|80|24|E|region:LK|display=inline,title}}\n}} \n'''Kilinochchi''' ({{lang-ta|\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0ba8\u0bca\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbf}}, [[IAST]] ''Kilinocci'', {{lang-si|\u0d9a\u0dd2\u0dbd\u0dd2\u0db1\u0ddc\u0da0\u0dca\u0da0\u0dd2}}) is the main town of [[Kilinochchi District]], [[Northern Province (Sri Lanka)|Northern Province]] of [[Sri Lanka]]. Kilinochchi is situated at the [[A 9 highway (Sri Lanka)|A9 road]] some {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-east of [[Jaffna]]. It was the administrative center and de facto capital of the [[LTTE]] (Tamil Tigers)<ref>IRIN (25 March 2010) [http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/215be6c2eca72a197c26f89b9c8c0255.htm \"Sri Lanka: Former rebel capital struggles with returnee influx\"] AlertNet, Reuters, accessed 25 March 2010, archived at [http://www.freezepage.com/1269538117NRGNVAAZDZ?url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId%3D88553 original IRIN page]</ref> until 2 January 2009, when troops of the [[Sri Lankan Army]] recaptured the city.\n\n==History==\n\n===Creation (1936)===\nThe Kilinochchi town was established in 1936 as part of a colonization project that sought to ease overpopulation and unemployment in Jaffna.<ref name=\"Kilicolonization\">{{Cite book | last = Manogaran  | first = Chelvadurai | authorlink = | coauthors =  | title = Ethnic conflicts and reconciliation in Sri Lanka | publisher = University of Hawaii Press | year = 1987 | location = | pages = 90| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=4IdR9N9R7T4C&pg=PA228&dq=Iranamadu+colony&hl=en&ei=6eLMS5n5JoqUMcD7haIF&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Iranamadu&f=false| doi = | id = | isbn = 0-8248-1116-X }}</ref>\n\nKilinochchi is still part of Jaffna electoral division and it was separated from the Jaffna district in the 1980s as a new district. Most of the people living in this district are farmers and related to agricultural work. Most of the people were migrated from Jaffna to acquire government grants for land and to engage in paddy (rice) cultivation. They were then migrated overseas (Europe, US, Canada, Australia, etc.) during the civil war (1990 onward). The population is rising again after the end of the civil war.\n\n===Sri Lankan Civil War===\n[[File:LTTE car with soldiers in Killinochi april 2004.jpg|thumb|left|[[LTTE]] troops in Kilinochchi, 2004]]\nThe LTTE first took hold of the town in 1990 when the Army withdrew its garrisons from Kilinochchi. Then the area was retaken by the Army during operations Sathjaya I, II, and III in September 1996. The town again fell into the LTTE's hand in September 1998 who held their administrative hub there until retreating during the [[Battle of Kilinochchi (2008\u20132009)|Battle of Kilinochchi]] on 2 January 2009.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7811360.stm \"Ruined remains of rebel 'capital'\"], BBC, January 5, 2009</ref>\n\nSeveral institutions of the LTTE were forced to relocate from Kilinochchi to [[Tharmapuram]], a town about 13&nbsp;km in the east, by early October, 2008 in fear of death by advancing government troops.\n\n==Demography==\nMost people living in Kilinochchi are [[Sri Lankan Tamils]].\n\n==Economy==\nKilinochchi is one of the major agrarian [[Tillage|cultivation]] destinations in the island from the [[pre-history|pre-historic]] times. [[Iranamadu Tank|Iranamadu (Ranamaduva)]] Tank, Kanakampikai Kulam (Pond), and Kilinochchi Kulam are the major [[irrigation]] source for [[Rice|paddy]] and various other cultivations.\n\n==Transport==\nKilinochchi is connected to the Sri Lanka railways northern line via its railway station.\n\n==Media==\nKilinochchi is served with all Jaffna- and Colombo-based newspapers. Jaffna-based ''[[Uthayan]] ''newspaper has a regional office in Kilinochchi.\n\nThere are allegations not to distribute Jaffna based newspapers in Vanni area especially the ''Uthayan'' newspaper. ''Uthayan'' is highly critical of inappropriate land acquisition in Jaffna peninsula and Vanni region by the Sri Lankan Military and Government.\n\n==Education==\nThis district has several Government Colleges such as [[Kilinochchi Central College]], Hindu College, Uruthirapuram Maha Vidiyalayam school, [[Vaddakkachchi Maha Vidyalayam]] school, etc.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|position=left|Kilinochchi}}\n\n{{Sri Lankan cities}}\n\n[[Category:Kilinochchi| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Karachchi DS Division]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See Template:Infobox Settlement for additional fields that may be available-->\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name                   = Kilinochchi\n|native_name            = \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0ba8\u0bca\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbf<br>\u0d9a\u0dd2\u0dbd\u0dd2\u0db1\u0ddc\u0da0\u0dca\u0da0\u0dd2\n|settlement_type        = [[Town]]\n|image_skyline          = Kilinochchi court of de-facto State Tamil Eelam.jpg\n|image_size             = 300px\n|image_caption          = Kilinochchi courthouse\n|pushpin_map            = Sri Lanka Northern Province\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = [[Sri Lanka]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Sri Lanka|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Northern Province (Sri Lanka)|Northern]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Sri Lanka|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Kilinochchi District|Kilinochchi]]\n|subdivision_type4 = [[Divisional Secretariats of Sri Lanka|DS Division]]\n|subdivision_name4 = Karachchi \n| population_as_of =\n| population_footnotes = \n| population_note = \n| population_total =\n|timezone = [[Time zone#UTC .2B 6.2C F|Sri Lanka Standard Time Zone]]\n|utc_offset = +5:30\n|timezone_DST = \n|utc_offset_DST = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|9|23|N|80|24|E|region:LK|display=inline,title}}\n}} \n'''Kilinochchi''' ({{lang-ta|\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0ba8\u0bca\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbf}}, [[IAST]] ''Kilinocci'', {{lang-si|\u0d9a\u0dd2\u0dbd\u0dd2\u0db1\u0ddc\u0da0\u0dca\u0da0\u0dd2}}) is the main town of [[Kilinochchi District]], [[Northern Province (Sri Lanka)|Northern Province]] of [[Sri Lanka]]. Kilinochchi is situated at the [[A 9 highway (Sri Lanka)|A9 road]] some {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-east of [[Jaffna]]. It was the administrative center and de facto capital of the [[LTTE]] (Tamil Tigers)<ref>IRIN (25 March 2010) [http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/215be6c2eca72a197c26f89b9c8c0255.htm \"Sri Lanka: Former rebel capital struggles with returnee influx\"] AlertNet, Reuters, accessed 25 March 2010, archived at [http://www.freezepage.com/1269538117NRGNVAAZDZ?url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId%3D88553 original IRIN page]</ref> until 2 January 2009, when troops of the [[Sri Lankan Army]] recaptured the city.\n\n==History==\n\n===Creation (1936)===\nThe Kilinochchi town was established in 1936 as part of a colonization project that sought to ease overpopulation and unemployment in Jaffna.<ref name=\"Kilicolonization\">{{Cite book | last = Manogaran  | first = Chelvadurai | authorlink = | coauthors =  | title = Ethnic conflicts and reconciliation in Sri Lanka | publisher = University of Hawaii Press | year = 1987 | location = | pages = 90| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=4IdR9N9R7T4C&pg=PA228&dq=Iranamadu+colony&hl=en&ei=6eLMS5n5JoqUMcD7haIF&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Iranamadu&f=false| doi = | id = | isbn = 0-8248-1116-X }}</ref>\n\nKilinochchi is still part of Jaffna electoral division and it was separated from the Jaffna district in the 1980s as a new district. Most of the people living in this district are farmers and related to agricultural work. Most of the people were migrated from Jaffna to acquire government grants for land and to engage in paddy (rice) cultivation. They were then migrated overseas (Europe, US, Canada, Australia, etc.) during the civil war (1990 onward). The population is rising again after the end of the civil war.\n\n===Sri Lankan Civil War===\n[[File:LTTE car with soldiers in Killinochi april 2004.jpg|thumb|left|[[LTTE]] troops in Kilinochchi, 2004]]\nThe LTTE first took hold of the town in 1990 when the Army withdrew its garrisons from Kilinochchi. Then the area was retaken by the Army during operations Sathjaya I, II, and III in September 1996. The town again fell into the LTTE's hand in September 1998 who held their administrative hub there until retreating during the [[Battle of Kilinochchi (2008\u20132009)|Battle of Kilinochchi]] on 2 January 2009.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7811360.stm \"Ruined remains of rebel 'capital'\"], BBC, January 5, 2009</ref>\n\nSeveral institutions of the LTTE were forced to relocate from Kilinochchi to [[Tharmapuram]], a town about 13&nbsp;km in the east, by early October, 2008 in fear of death by advancing government troops.\n\n==Demography==\nMost people living in Kilinochchi are [[Sri Lankan Tamils]].\n\n==Economy==\nKilinochchi is one of the major agrarian [[Tillage|cultivation]] destinations in the island from the [[pre-history|pre-historic]] times. [[Iranamadu Tank|Iranamadu (Ranamaduva)]] Tank, Kanakampikai Kulam (Pond), and Kilinochchi Kulam are the major [[irrigation]] source for [[Rice|paddy]] and various other cultivations.\n\n==Transport==\nKilinochchi is connected to the Sri Lanka railways northern line via its railway station.\n\n==Media==\nKilinochchi is served with all Jaffna- and Colombo-based newspapers. Jaffna-based ''[[Uthayan]] ''newspaper has a regional office in Kilinochchi.\n\nThere are allegations not to distribute Jaffna based newspapers in Vanni area especially the ''Uthayan'' newspaper. ''Uthayan'' is highly critical of inappropriate land acquisition in Jaffna peninsula and Vanni region by the Sri Lankan Military and Government.\n\n==Education==\nThis district has several Government Colleges such as [[Kilinochchi Central College]], Hindu College, Uruthirapuram Maha Vidiyalayam school, [[Vaddakkachchi Maha Vidyalayam]] school, etc.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|position=left|Kilinochchi}}\n\n{{Sri Lankan cities}}\n\n[[Category:Kilinochchi| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Karachchi DS Division]]\n", "name_user": "37.175.57.177", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilinochchi"}
{"title_page": "Black women", "text_new": "[[File:Kamala Harris with women - Feb 2020.jpg|thumb|A group of Black women, including Senator [[Kamala Harris]], in 2020.]]\n'''Black women''' are women who are of African and Afro-diasporic descent. The term black women is both a multi-faceted cultural identity and a powerful social construct with different meanings in different places. A well known black woman is LeBron James, who cries after every call that doesn\u2019t go his way.\n\n==Black internationalism==\nIdeas of black internationalism have expanded since the 1920s. Blain and Gill define it as \"a global political, intellectual, and artistic movement of African-descended people engaged in a collective struggle to overthrow global white supremacy in its many forms\". Black women have played a major role in numerous countries.<ref>Keisha N. Blain and Tiffany M. Gill, eds. ''To Turn the Whole World Over: Black Women and Internationalism'' (U of Illinois Press, 2019) p. 2.</ref>\n\n== United States ==\n\n=== Black women in popular culture ===\nNotable black women in US popular culture include, but are not limited to, the following:\n*[[File:(Portrait of Harriet Tubman) (LOC) (38899567180).jpg|thumb|Portrait of Harriet Tubman]][[Harriet Tubman]]: Born in the early 19th century in the former slave state of Maryland, Tubman is widely regarded for helping many African-American slaves to escape slavery via the [[Underground Railroad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/black-culture/explore/harriet-tubman/#.WRu1pfryufQ|title=Harriet Tubman Facts and Quotes {{!}} Black History {{!}} PBS|website=Harriet Tubman Facts and Quotes {{!}} Black History {{!}} PBS|access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref> According to [[PBS]], Tubman risked her own life \"19 times by 1860\" in order to save other slaves and return them to the North during the [[American Civil War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/aia/part4/4p1535.html|title=Harriet Tubman|website=www.pbs.org|access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref> Prior to being married, Tubman's name was Araminta Ross<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/activist/harriet-tubman|title=Harriet Tubman|website=Biography|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> and she was also a nurse, cook and spy for the Northern Army during the Civil War.\n*[[File:Ella Fitzgerald (Gottlieb 02871).jpg|thumb|Ella Fitzgerald]][[Ella Fitzgerald]]: Fitzgerald, an American Jazz singer born in 1917, was given the title of \"The First Lady of Song.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ellafitzgerald.com/|title=Ella Fitzgerald|website=Ella Fitzgerald|language=en|access-date=2017-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220142107/http://www.ellafitzgerald.com/|archive-date=2014-02-20|url-status=dead}}</ref> Fitzgerald is also known as the Queen of Jazz and won 13 Grammys for her vocal performances over the course of her life. In the music community, Fitzgerald is known for her four octave [[vocal range]] and for being a [[Scat singing|scat]]-singer. Additionally, Fitzgerald was capable of performing music in a multitude of genres, including [[Swing music|swing]] and [[Bop jazz|bop]].<ref name=\"DeVeaux\">{{Cite book|title=Jazz|last=DeVeaux|first=Scott|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2009|isbn=9780393192742|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> Like many black artists at the time, Fitzgerald performed at the Apollo Theater in New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/ella-fitzgerald-wins-amateur-night-at-harlems-apollo-theater|title=Ella Fitzgerald wins Amateur Night at Harlem's Apollo Theater|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[File:Billie Holiday, Downbeat, New York, N.Y., ca. Feb. 1947 (William P. Gottlieb 04251).jpg|thumb|Billie Holiday, Downbeat, New York, N.Y., ca. Feb. 1947 ]][[Billie Holiday]]: Similar to Fitzgerald, Holiday, born as Eleanora Fagan, remains an important figure within the history of jazz music in America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/billie-holiday-9341902|title=Billie Holiday|website=Biography.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref> Influenced by [[Louis Armstrong]], Holiday's vocal range was limited yet she is known for her thin, light voice that has a punch to it. Holiday is featured on the track \"A Sailboat in the Moonlight\" which was a number one hit when it was released and remains popular today,.<ref name=\"DeVeaux\" />\n*[[File:072213 Queen Latifah.webm|thumb|Queen Latifah in 2013]]: [[Queen Latifah]]: Real name Dana Elaine Owens, Queen Latifah is an American singer, songwriter, actor, and producer. She has released 7 solo [[:Category:Queen Latifah albums|studio albums]] in addition to 1 [[:Category:Queen Latifah albums|compilation album]]. She is known for her energetic, smooth, and skillful rapping style. In 1993, her acting career took off with her starring role as Khadijah James on the FOX television series [[Living Single|Living Single.]] From there, Owens obtained supporting roles in the films ''[[House Party 2]]'' (1991), ''[[Jungle Fever]]'' (1991), and ''[[Juice (film)|Juice]]'' (1992). Since then, Owens has achieved superstar status as a talk show host ([[The Queen Latifah Show]]) and mainstream actor [[Chicago (2002 film)|(''Chicago'' (2002),]] [[Bringing Down the House (film)|''Bringing Down the House'' (2003)]], [[Scary Movie 3|''Scary Movie 3'' (2003)]], [[Taxi (2004 film)|''Taxi'' (2004)]], [[Hairspray (2007 film)|''Hairspray'' (2007)]] and many [[List of awards and nominations received by Queen Latifah|more]]).\n*[[File:Oprah in 2014.jpg|thumb|Oprah Winfrey in 2014]][[Oprah Winfrey]]: One of the most famous women on the planet, Oprah Winfrey is a TV host/producer, philanthropist, and media mogul. She is perhaps best known for [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]], which has run for 25 seasons since 1986 and maintained a weekly viewership well into the tens of millions. She is the namesake of the [[Oprah Winfrey Network]] (OWN), which produces content largely targeted at black audiences. According to [https://www.forbes.com/profile/oprah-winfrey/#71ead2495745 Forbes], she has a current net worth of approximately 2.7 billion USD, one of the wealthiest self-made fortunes of all time.\n*[[File:Beyonce cropped2.jpg|thumb|[[Beyonc\u00e9]] Knowles Carter]][[Beyonc\u00e9]]: Full name Beyonc\u00e9 Giselle Knowles-Carter, Beyonc\u00e9 is an American singer, songwriter, producer, philanthropist, dancer, and actor. Her first major venture in the music industry was as the frontwoman of [[Destiny's Child]]. The group released 5 studio albums from 1998 to 2004. As a solo act, she has released 9 studio albums from 2003 to [[Beyonc\u00e9 discography|2019]]. \n\n[[File:Congressional Black Caucus women 2019.jpg|thumb|Congressional Black Caucus women in 2019]]\n\n=== US Politics ===\nBlack women in US political history include, but are not limited to, the following:\n\n* [[Shirley Chisholm|Shirley Chisholm:]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womenshistory.org/education-resources/biographies/shirley-chisholm|title=Shirley Chisholm|last=|first=|date=|website=womenshistory.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Chisholm was the first African-American woman to serve in Congress as well as the first to run for President of the United States on the ticket of a major political party. She served in [[New York's 12th congressional district]] for seven terms from 1969 to 1983. \n* [[Barbara Jordan]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/law-figure/barbara-jordan|title=Barbara Jordan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=biography.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://history.house.gov/People/Detail/16031|title=JORDAN, Barbara Charline|last=|first=|date=|website=History, Art, and Archives: United States House of Representatives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Jordan was the first African-American congresswoman from the [[Deep South]], originating from Houston, Texas. She was also the first black woman elected to the [[Texas Senate]] in 1966. \n* [[Kamala Harris]]: Harris was elected to the US Senate as a representative of California in 2016. In January 2019, Harris officially announced her candidacy for President of the United States, but fell short of campaign funds in late 2019 and was forced to drop out of the race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/03/784443227/kamala-harris-drops-out-of-presidential-race|title=Kamala Harris Drops Out of Presidential Race|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== [[Slavery in the United States|American Slavery]] ===\nBlack [[Slavery in the United States|slaves]], many of whom were women, were often abused by their owners and other [[White Americans|white people]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Greenberg|first1=Kenneth S|last2=White|first2=Deborah Gray|last3=Harris|first3=J. William|year=1987|title=Black Women and White Men in the Antebellum South|journal=Reviews in American History|volume=15|issue=2|pages=252|doi=10.2307/2702176|jstor=2702176}}</ref> This abuse extended beyond the physical and psychological abuse directly related to how slaves were treated, and include the exploitation of black women slaves in order to advance different scientific practices and techniques.{{fact|date=December 2018}} Black female slaves were sexually abused by White men and were forced to breed with their White male slave masters to bear [[mulatto]] children to maintain [[White supremacy]], have more slaves to pick cotton and produce superior slaves in [[Southern United States|the South]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://courses.lumenlearning.com/boundless-ushistory/chapter/slavery-in-the-u-s/|title=Slavery in the U.S. &#124; Boundless US History|website=courses.lumenlearning.com}}</ref> Black female slaves received the same treatment in Brazil, [[Hispanic America]] and [[the Caribbean]].<ref> see \"American Slavery in Comparative Perspective\" (2019)[http://www.digitalhistory.uh.edu/disp_textbook.cfm?smtid=2&psid=3044 online]</ref><ref>David Gaspar and Darlene Clark Hine, eds. ''More than chattel: Black women and slavery in the Americas'' (Indiana UP, 1996).</ref>\n\nMany historical scholars argue \n\n=== Increased risk for health problems ===\nBlack women are often at a higher risk to contract these diseases than white women, but they also are at a higher risk to die from them as well. According to the American Cancer Society, the death rate for all cancers for black women is 14% higher than that of white women<ref name=\"cancer\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cancer.org/content/dam/cancer-org/research/cancer-facts-and-statistics/cancer-facts-and-figures-for-african-americans/cancer-facts-and-figures-for-african-americans-2016-2018.pdf|title=Cancer Facts & Figures for African Americans}}</ref>. While the probability of being diagnosed with cancer in black women is 1 in 3, the chance of dying from cancer is 1 in 5<ref name=\"cancer\" />. Cancer is not the only disease that disproportionately affects African American women. Lupus is 2-3 times more common in women of color, but more specifically 1 in every 537 black women will have lupus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lupus.org/resources/lupus-facts-and-statistics|title=Lupus facts and statistics|website=Lupus Foundation of America|language=en|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref> Black women are also at a higher chance of being overweight thus making them open to more obesity-related diseases.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gillum|first=Richard F.|date=1987\u20132008|title=Overweight and Obesity in Black Women: A Review of Published Data From The National Center for Health Statistics|journal=Journal of the National Medical Association|volume=79|issue=8|pages=865\u2013871|issn=0027-9684|pmc=2625572|pmid=3508218}}</ref> There is also a racial disparity when it comes to pregnancy related deaths. While there are 12.4 deaths for every 100,000 births for white women, the statistics for black women is 40.0 deaths for every 100,000 births.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/reproductivehealth/maternalinfanthealth/pregnancy-mortality-surveillance-system.htm|title=Pregnancy Mortality Surveillance System {{!}} Maternal and Infant Health {{!}} CDC|date=2018-08-07|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref>\n\n== Famous leaders ==\n[[File:Ellen Johnson Sirleaf February 2015.jpg|thumb|Right|President Ellen Sirleaf-Johnson of Liberia]]\nSome of the most important artistic and political leaders in history have been black women. For instance, Queen [[Qalhata]] and [[Candace of Meroe]]&nbsp;are important, early African queens.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Na4QAQAAMAAJ&q=Qalhata&dq=Qalhata|title=The Image of the Black in Western art|last=Vercoutter|first=Jean|date=1976-01-01|publisher=Morrow|isbn=9780688030865|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=466fAAAAMAAJ&q=Qalhata+candace&dq=Qalhata+candace|title=When We Ruled: The Ancient and Medi\u0153val History of Black Civilisations|last=Walker|first=Robin|date=2006-01-01|publisher=Every Generation Media|isbn=9780955106804|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ol9X2G2ub24C&dq=Qalhata+candace|title=Black Women in Antiquity|last=Sertima|first=Ivan Van|date=1984-01-01|publisher=Transaction Books|isbn=9780878559824|language=en}}</ref> In the United States, [[Toni Morrison]] was the first black woman Nobel laureate. [[Shirley Chisholm]] was an important Democratic candidate for U.S. President in the 1970s. In Africa, President [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]] served as President of Liberia for 12 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/ellen-johnson-sirleaf/#532d49fe44fb|title=Ellen Johnson Sirleaf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Caribbean society==\nJennifer Palmer argues that in the plantation world of the colonial Caribbean, women of color Were typically treated as property owned by white men. In the French islands, race and gender shape popular Assumptions about who could own property. However there were legal loopholes that sometimes  opened up windows of opportunity for women of color to be landowners.<ref>Jennifer L. Palmer,  \"The fruits of their labours: Race, gender and labour in the eighteenth-century French Caribbean.\" ''French History'' 32.4 (2018): 471-492.</ref>\n==Africa==\n{{Main|Maputo Protocol}}\nThe 2003 Maputo Protocol on women's rights in Africa set the continental standard for progressive expansion of women's rights. It  guarantees comprehensive rights to women including the right to take part in the political process, to social and political equality with men, improved autonomy in their reproductive health decisions, and an end to female genital mutilation.<ref>Christine Ocran,  \"The Protocol to the African Charter on Human and Peoples' Rights on the Rights of Women in Africa.\" ''African Journal of International and Comparative Law'' 15.1 (2007): 147-152.</ref>\n=== Ghana===\nWomen play a modest role in Ghana's two major political parties: NDC (National Democratic Congress) and NPP (New Patriotic Party) \u2013 as well as the small party CPP (Convention People's Party). The first president, [[Kwame Nkrumah]] (CPP) made Ghana the first African nation to introduce a quota in 1959, reserving ten seats for women in Parliament. Ghana has recently been laggard, however, with a representation of 11% women after the election in 2012 and 13% after the election in 2016.<ref>Diana H\u00f8jlund Madsen, \"Gender, Power and Institutional Change\u2013The Role of Formal and Informal Institutions in Promoting Women\u2019s Political Representation in Ghana.\" ''Journal of Asian and African Studies'' 54.1 (2019): 70-87.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[African-American women in politics]]\n* [[African National Congress Women's League]]\n* [[African Women's Union of the Congo]]\n*[[History of Africa]]\n*[[African diaspora#History|History of the African diaspora]], particularly:\n**[[African-American history]], for the United States\n**[[Afro-Arab|History of Afro-Arab peoples]]\n**[[Afro-Brazilian history]]\n**[[Black British|History of Black British people]]\n**[[Black Canadians#History|History of Black Canadians]]\n**[[Afro-Caribbean history]]\n**[[Afro-Latin American#History|History of Afro-Latin Americans]]\n*[[Reproductive rights]]\n*[[Women's rights]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Blain, Keisha N.  and Tiffany M. Gill, eds. ''To Turn the Whole World Over: Black Women and Internationalism'' (U of Illinois Press, 2019). 280 pp. [http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showpdf.php?id=54212 online review]\n* Blain, Keisha N. ''Set the World on Fire: Black Nationalist Women and the Global Struggle for Freedom'' (U of Pennsylvania Press, 2018)\n* Coquery-Vidrovitc, Catherine. ''African Women: A Modern History'' (1997) [https://www.amazon.com/African-Women-History-Catherine-Coquery-vidrovitch-dp-036731438X/dp/036731438X/  excerpt]\n* Hafkin, Nancy, and Edna G. Bay. ''Women in Africa: Studies in social and economic change'' (Stanford UP, 1976).\n* Harris-Perry, Melissa V. ''Sister citizen: Shame, stereotypes, and Black women in America'' (Yale UP, 2011).\n* Hine, Darlene Clark, and Kathleen Thompson. ''A shining thread of hope: The history of Black women in America'' (1999).\n* Hooks, Bell. ''Ain't I A Woman: Black women and feminism'' (Routledge, 2014).\n* Jones, Jacqueline. ''Labor of Love, Labor of Sorrow: Black Women, Work, and the Family, from Slavery to the Present'' (2nd ed. 2010) [https://www.amazon.com/Labor-Love-Sorrow-Slavery-Present/dp/0465018815/  excerpt]\n* Nelson, Nicki. ''African women in the development process'' (Routledge, 2013).\n* Scales-Trent, Judy. \"Black women and the constitution: Finding our place, asserting our rights.\" ''Harvard Civil Rights-Civil Liberties Law Review''  24 (1989): 9-44. [https://digitalcommons.law.buffalo.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1791&context=articles online]\n* Smith, Barbara, ed. ''Home girls: A black feminist anthology'' (Rutgers UP, 2000), primary sources.\n* Stichter, Sharon B., and Jane Parpart. ''Patriarchy and class: African women in the home and the workforce'' (Routledge, 2019).\n* Strobel, Margaret. \"African women.\" ''Signs: Journal of Women in Culture and Society'' 8.1 (1982): 109-131.\n* Vaz, Kim Marie, ed. ''Black women in America'' (Sage Publications, 1994).\n\n[[Category:Black (human racial classification)]]\n[[Category:People of African descent]]\n[[Category:Women]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Kamala Harris with women - Feb 2020.jpg|thumb|A group of Black women, including Senator [[Kamala Harris]], in 2020.]]\n'''Black women''' are women who are of African and Afro-diasporic descent. The term black women is both a multi-faceted cultural identity and a powerful social construct with different meanings in different places.\n\n==Black internationalism==\nIdeas of black internationalism have expanded since the 1920s. Blain and Gill define it as \"a global political, intellectual, and artistic movement of African-descended people engaged in a collective struggle to overthrow global white supremacy in its many forms\". Black women have played a major role in numerous countries.<ref>Keisha N. Blain and Tiffany M. Gill, eds. ''To Turn the Whole World Over: Black Women and Internationalism'' (U of Illinois Press, 2019) p. 2.</ref>\n\n== United States ==\n\n=== Black women in popular culture ===\nNotable black women in US popular culture include, but are not limited to, the following:\n*[[File:(Portrait of Harriet Tubman) (LOC) (38899567180).jpg|thumb|Portrait of Harriet Tubman]][[Harriet Tubman]]: Born in the early 19th century in the former slave state of Maryland, Tubman is widely regarded for helping many African-American slaves to escape slavery via the [[Underground Railroad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/black-culture/explore/harriet-tubman/#.WRu1pfryufQ|title=Harriet Tubman Facts and Quotes {{!}} Black History {{!}} PBS|website=Harriet Tubman Facts and Quotes {{!}} Black History {{!}} PBS|access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref> According to [[PBS]], Tubman risked her own life \"19 times by 1860\" in order to save other slaves and return them to the North during the [[American Civil War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/aia/part4/4p1535.html|title=Harriet Tubman|website=www.pbs.org|access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref> Prior to being married, Tubman's name was Araminta Ross<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/activist/harriet-tubman|title=Harriet Tubman|website=Biography|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> and she was also a nurse, cook and spy for the Northern Army during the Civil War.\n*[[File:Ella Fitzgerald (Gottlieb 02871).jpg|thumb|Ella Fitzgerald]][[Ella Fitzgerald]]: Fitzgerald, an American Jazz singer born in 1917, was given the title of \"The First Lady of Song.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ellafitzgerald.com/|title=Ella Fitzgerald|website=Ella Fitzgerald|language=en|access-date=2017-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220142107/http://www.ellafitzgerald.com/|archive-date=2014-02-20|url-status=dead}}</ref> Fitzgerald is also known as the Queen of Jazz and won 13 Grammys for her vocal performances over the course of her life. In the music community, Fitzgerald is known for her four octave [[vocal range]] and for being a [[Scat singing|scat]]-singer. Additionally, Fitzgerald was capable of performing music in a multitude of genres, including [[Swing music|swing]] and [[Bop jazz|bop]].<ref name=\"DeVeaux\">{{Cite book|title=Jazz|last=DeVeaux|first=Scott|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2009|isbn=9780393192742|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> Like many black artists at the time, Fitzgerald performed at the Apollo Theater in New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/ella-fitzgerald-wins-amateur-night-at-harlems-apollo-theater|title=Ella Fitzgerald wins Amateur Night at Harlem's Apollo Theater|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[File:Billie Holiday, Downbeat, New York, N.Y., ca. Feb. 1947 (William P. Gottlieb 04251).jpg|thumb|Billie Holiday, Downbeat, New York, N.Y., ca. Feb. 1947 ]][[Billie Holiday]]: Similar to Fitzgerald, Holiday, born as Eleanora Fagan, remains an important figure within the history of jazz music in America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/billie-holiday-9341902|title=Billie Holiday|website=Biography.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref> Influenced by [[Louis Armstrong]], Holiday's vocal range was limited yet she is known for her thin, light voice that has a punch to it. Holiday is featured on the track \"A Sailboat in the Moonlight\" which was a number one hit when it was released and remains popular today,.<ref name=\"DeVeaux\" />\n*[[File:072213 Queen Latifah.webm|thumb|Queen Latifah in 2013]]: [[Queen Latifah]]: Real name Dana Elaine Owens, Queen Latifah is an American singer, songwriter, actor, and producer. She has released 7 solo [[:Category:Queen Latifah albums|studio albums]] in addition to 1 [[:Category:Queen Latifah albums|compilation album]]. She is known for her energetic, smooth, and skillful rapping style. In 1993, her acting career took off with her starring role as Khadijah James on the FOX television series [[Living Single|Living Single.]] From there, Owens obtained supporting roles in the films ''[[House Party 2]]'' (1991), ''[[Jungle Fever]]'' (1991), and ''[[Juice (film)|Juice]]'' (1992). Since then, Owens has achieved superstar status as a talk show host ([[The Queen Latifah Show]]) and mainstream actor [[Chicago (2002 film)|(''Chicago'' (2002),]] [[Bringing Down the House (film)|''Bringing Down the House'' (2003)]], [[Scary Movie 3|''Scary Movie 3'' (2003)]], [[Taxi (2004 film)|''Taxi'' (2004)]], [[Hairspray (2007 film)|''Hairspray'' (2007)]] and many [[List of awards and nominations received by Queen Latifah|more]]).\n*[[File:Oprah in 2014.jpg|thumb|Oprah Winfrey in 2014]][[Oprah Winfrey]]: One of the most famous women on the planet, Oprah Winfrey is a TV host/producer, philanthropist, and media mogul. She is perhaps best known for [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]], which has run for 25 seasons since 1986 and maintained a weekly viewership well into the tens of millions. She is the namesake of the [[Oprah Winfrey Network]] (OWN), which produces content largely targeted at black audiences. According to [https://www.forbes.com/profile/oprah-winfrey/#71ead2495745 Forbes], she has a current net worth of approximately 2.7 billion USD, one of the wealthiest self-made fortunes of all time.\n*[[File:Beyonce cropped2.jpg|thumb|[[Beyonc\u00e9]] Knowles Carter]][[Beyonc\u00e9]]: Full name Beyonc\u00e9 Giselle Knowles-Carter, Beyonc\u00e9 is an American singer, songwriter, producer, philanthropist, dancer, and actor. Her first major venture in the music industry was as the frontwoman of [[Destiny's Child]]. The group released 5 studio albums from 1998 to 2004. As a solo act, she has released 9 studio albums from 2003 to [[Beyonc\u00e9 discography|2019]]. \n\n[[File:Congressional Black Caucus women 2019.jpg|thumb|Congressional Black Caucus women in 2019]]\n\n=== US Politics ===\nBlack women in US political history include, but are not limited to, the following:\n\n* [[Shirley Chisholm|Shirley Chisholm:]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womenshistory.org/education-resources/biographies/shirley-chisholm|title=Shirley Chisholm|last=|first=|date=|website=womenshistory.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Chisholm was the first African-American woman to serve in Congress as well as the first to run for President of the United States on the ticket of a major political party. She served in [[New York's 12th congressional district]] for seven terms from 1969 to 1983. \n* [[Barbara Jordan]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/law-figure/barbara-jordan|title=Barbara Jordan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=biography.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://history.house.gov/People/Detail/16031|title=JORDAN, Barbara Charline|last=|first=|date=|website=History, Art, and Archives: United States House of Representatives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Jordan was the first African-American congresswoman from the [[Deep South]], originating from Houston, Texas. She was also the first black woman elected to the [[Texas Senate]] in 1966. \n* [[Kamala Harris]]: Harris was elected to the US Senate as a representative of California in 2016. In January 2019, Harris officially announced her candidacy for President of the United States, but fell short of campaign funds in late 2019 and was forced to drop out of the race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/03/784443227/kamala-harris-drops-out-of-presidential-race|title=Kamala Harris Drops Out of Presidential Race|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== [[Slavery in the United States|American Slavery]] ===\nBlack [[Slavery in the United States|slaves]], many of whom were women, were often abused by their owners and other [[White Americans|white people]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Greenberg|first1=Kenneth S|last2=White|first2=Deborah Gray|last3=Harris|first3=J. William|year=1987|title=Black Women and White Men in the Antebellum South|journal=Reviews in American History|volume=15|issue=2|pages=252|doi=10.2307/2702176|jstor=2702176}}</ref> This abuse extended beyond the physical and psychological abuse directly related to how slaves were treated, and include the exploitation of black women slaves in order to advance different scientific practices and techniques.{{fact|date=December 2018}} Black female slaves were sexually abused by White men and were forced to breed with their White male slave masters to bear [[mulatto]] children to maintain [[White supremacy]], have more slaves to pick cotton and produce superior slaves in [[Southern United States|the South]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://courses.lumenlearning.com/boundless-ushistory/chapter/slavery-in-the-u-s/|title=Slavery in the U.S. &#124; Boundless US History|website=courses.lumenlearning.com}}</ref> Black female slaves received the same treatment in Brazil, [[Hispanic America]] and [[the Caribbean]].<ref> see \"American Slavery in Comparative Perspective\" (2019)[http://www.digitalhistory.uh.edu/disp_textbook.cfm?smtid=2&psid=3044 online]</ref><ref>David Gaspar and Darlene Clark Hine, eds. ''More than chattel: Black women and slavery in the Americas'' (Indiana UP, 1996).</ref>\n\nMany historical scholars argue \n\n=== Increased risk for health problems ===\nBlack women are often at a higher risk to contract these diseases than white women, but they also are at a higher risk to die from them as well. According to the American Cancer Society, the death rate for all cancers for black women is 14% higher than that of white women<ref name=\"cancer\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cancer.org/content/dam/cancer-org/research/cancer-facts-and-statistics/cancer-facts-and-figures-for-african-americans/cancer-facts-and-figures-for-african-americans-2016-2018.pdf|title=Cancer Facts & Figures for African Americans}}</ref>. While the probability of being diagnosed with cancer in black women is 1 in 3, the chance of dying from cancer is 1 in 5<ref name=\"cancer\" />. Cancer is not the only disease that disproportionately affects African American women. Lupus is 2-3 times more common in women of color, but more specifically 1 in every 537 black women will have lupus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lupus.org/resources/lupus-facts-and-statistics|title=Lupus facts and statistics|website=Lupus Foundation of America|language=en|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref> Black women are also at a higher chance of being overweight thus making them open to more obesity-related diseases.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gillum|first=Richard F.|date=1987\u20132008|title=Overweight and Obesity in Black Women: A Review of Published Data From The National Center for Health Statistics|journal=Journal of the National Medical Association|volume=79|issue=8|pages=865\u2013871|issn=0027-9684|pmc=2625572|pmid=3508218}}</ref> There is also a racial disparity when it comes to pregnancy related deaths. While there are 12.4 deaths for every 100,000 births for white women, the statistics for black women is 40.0 deaths for every 100,000 births.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/reproductivehealth/maternalinfanthealth/pregnancy-mortality-surveillance-system.htm|title=Pregnancy Mortality Surveillance System {{!}} Maternal and Infant Health {{!}} CDC|date=2018-08-07|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref>\n\n== Famous leaders ==\n[[File:Ellen Johnson Sirleaf February 2015.jpg|thumb|Right|President Ellen Sirleaf-Johnson of Liberia]]\nSome of the most important artistic and political leaders in history have been black women. For instance, Queen [[Qalhata]] and [[Candace of Meroe]]&nbsp;are important, early African queens.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Na4QAQAAMAAJ&q=Qalhata&dq=Qalhata|title=The Image of the Black in Western art|last=Vercoutter|first=Jean|date=1976-01-01|publisher=Morrow|isbn=9780688030865|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=466fAAAAMAAJ&q=Qalhata+candace&dq=Qalhata+candace|title=When We Ruled: The Ancient and Medi\u0153val History of Black Civilisations|last=Walker|first=Robin|date=2006-01-01|publisher=Every Generation Media|isbn=9780955106804|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ol9X2G2ub24C&dq=Qalhata+candace|title=Black Women in Antiquity|last=Sertima|first=Ivan Van|date=1984-01-01|publisher=Transaction Books|isbn=9780878559824|language=en}}</ref> In the United States, [[Toni Morrison]] was the first black woman Nobel laureate. [[Shirley Chisholm]] was an important Democratic candidate for U.S. President in the 1970s. In Africa, President [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]] served as President of Liberia for 12 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/ellen-johnson-sirleaf/#532d49fe44fb|title=Ellen Johnson Sirleaf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Caribbean society==\nJennifer Palmer argues that in the plantation world of the colonial Caribbean, women of color Were typically treated as property owned by white men. In the French islands, race and gender shape popular Assumptions about who could own property. However there were legal loopholes that sometimes  opened up windows of opportunity for women of color to be landowners.<ref>Jennifer L. Palmer,  \"The fruits of their labours: Race, gender and labour in the eighteenth-century French Caribbean.\" ''French History'' 32.4 (2018): 471-492.</ref>\n==Africa==\n{{Main|Maputo Protocol}}\nThe 2003 Maputo Protocol on women's rights in Africa set the continental standard for progressive expansion of women's rights. It  guarantees comprehensive rights to women including the right to take part in the political process, to social and political equality with men, improved autonomy in their reproductive health decisions, and an end to female genital mutilation.<ref>Christine Ocran,  \"The Protocol to the African Charter on Human and Peoples' Rights on the Rights of Women in Africa.\" ''African Journal of International and Comparative Law'' 15.1 (2007): 147-152.</ref>\n=== Ghana===\nWomen play a modest role in Ghana's two major political parties: NDC (National Democratic Congress) and NPP (New Patriotic Party) \u2013 as well as the small party CPP (Convention People's Party). The first president, [[Kwame Nkrumah]] (CPP) made Ghana the first African nation to introduce a quota in 1959, reserving ten seats for women in Parliament. Ghana has recently been laggard, however, with a representation of 11% women after the election in 2012 and 13% after the election in 2016.<ref>Diana H\u00f8jlund Madsen, \"Gender, Power and Institutional Change\u2013The Role of Formal and Informal Institutions in Promoting Women\u2019s Political Representation in Ghana.\" ''Journal of Asian and African Studies'' 54.1 (2019): 70-87.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[African-American women in politics]]\n* [[African National Congress Women's League]]\n* [[African Women's Union of the Congo]]\n*[[History of Africa]]\n*[[African diaspora#History|History of the African diaspora]], particularly:\n**[[African-American history]], for the United States\n**[[Afro-Arab|History of Afro-Arab peoples]]\n**[[Afro-Brazilian history]]\n**[[Black British|History of Black British people]]\n**[[Black Canadians#History|History of Black Canadians]]\n**[[Afro-Caribbean history]]\n**[[Afro-Latin American#History|History of Afro-Latin Americans]]\n*[[Reproductive rights]]\n*[[Women's rights]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Blain, Keisha N.  and Tiffany M. Gill, eds. ''To Turn the Whole World Over: Black Women and Internationalism'' (U of Illinois Press, 2019). 280 pp. [http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showpdf.php?id=54212 online review]\n* Blain, Keisha N. ''Set the World on Fire: Black Nationalist Women and the Global Struggle for Freedom'' (U of Pennsylvania Press, 2018)\n* Coquery-Vidrovitc, Catherine. ''African Women: A Modern History'' (1997) [https://www.amazon.com/African-Women-History-Catherine-Coquery-vidrovitch-dp-036731438X/dp/036731438X/  excerpt]\n* Hafkin, Nancy, and Edna G. Bay. ''Women in Africa: Studies in social and economic change'' (Stanford UP, 1976).\n* Harris-Perry, Melissa V. ''Sister citizen: Shame, stereotypes, and Black women in America'' (Yale UP, 2011).\n* Hine, Darlene Clark, and Kathleen Thompson. ''A shining thread of hope: The history of Black women in America'' (1999).\n* Hooks, Bell. ''Ain't I A Woman: Black women and feminism'' (Routledge, 2014).\n* Jones, Jacqueline. ''Labor of Love, Labor of Sorrow: Black Women, Work, and the Family, from Slavery to the Present'' (2nd ed. 2010) [https://www.amazon.com/Labor-Love-Sorrow-Slavery-Present/dp/0465018815/  excerpt]\n* Nelson, Nicki. ''African women in the development process'' (Routledge, 2013).\n* Scales-Trent, Judy. \"Black women and the constitution: Finding our place, asserting our rights.\" ''Harvard Civil Rights-Civil Liberties Law Review''  24 (1989): 9-44. [https://digitalcommons.law.buffalo.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1791&context=articles online]\n* Smith, Barbara, ed. ''Home girls: A black feminist anthology'' (Rutgers UP, 2000), primary sources.\n* Stichter, Sharon B., and Jane Parpart. ''Patriarchy and class: African women in the home and the workforce'' (Routledge, 2019).\n* Strobel, Margaret. \"African women.\" ''Signs: Journal of Women in Culture and Society'' 8.1 (1982): 109-131.\n* Vaz, Kim Marie, ed. ''Black women in America'' (Sage Publications, 1994).\n\n[[Category:Black (human racial classification)]]\n[[Category:People of African descent]]\n[[Category:Women]]\n", "name_user": "104.189.113.251", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_women"}
{"title_page": "Marcus Robinson (American football)", "text_new": "{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Marcus Robinson\n|image=\n|position=[[Wide Receiver]]\n|number=88, 87\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1975|2|27}}\n|height_ft= 6\n|height_in= 3\n|weight_lb= 215\n|birth_place=[[Fort Valley, Georgia]]\n|high_school=[[Peach County High School|Peach County]]<br/>([[Fort Valley, Georgia]])\n|college=[[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]]\n|draftyear=1997\n|draftround=4\n|draftpick=108\n|teams=\n* [[Chicago Bears]] ([[1997 NFL season|1997]]\u2013[[2002 NFL season|2002]])\n* [[Rhein Fire]] (1998)\n* [[Baltimore Ravens]] ([[2003 NFL season|2003]])\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ([[2004 NFL season|2004]]\u2013[[2006 NFL season|2006]])\n* [[Detroit Lions]] ([[2007 NFL season|2007]])*\n| highlights =\n* [[World Bowl VI]] (1998)\n* [[NFL Europe]] MVP (1998)\n| pastteamsnote = yes\n|statlabel1=[[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n|statvalue1=325\n|statlabel2=Receiving yards\n|statvalue2=4,699\n|statlabel3=Receiving [[touchdown]]s\n|statvalue3=43\n|nfl=ROB627446\n|pfr=R/RobiMa00\n}}\n\n'''Marcus Antonio Robinson''' (born February 27, 1975) is an [[Americans|American]] former [[American football|football]] player in the [[National Football League|NFL]], who played the position of [[wide receiver]].\n\nHe has played for the [[Chicago Bears]], the [[Baltimore Ravens]], and the [[Minnesota Vikings]], as well as the [[Rhein Fire]]. He founded the Marcus Robinson Foundation for underprivileged children.\n\n==Early life==\nRobinson was born in [[Fort Valley, Georgia|Fort Valley]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and attended Peach County High School in Fort Valley, where he starred in [[High school football|football]] and [[Track and field|track]]. In football, he won [[All-America]] and All-State honors as a [[wide receiver]], [[free safety]], and [[Punter (American football)|punter]]. In track, he won regional titles on the [[100m|100]] and [[200m|200]] meter dashes.\n\n==College career==\nRobinson played wide receiver at the [[University of South Carolina]].\n\n==Professional career==\nRobinson was drafted by the Chicago Bears in the 4th round (108th overall) of the 1997 NFL Draft.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/R/RobiMa00.htm|title= Marcus Robinson  | publisher= Pro-Football-Reference.Com |accessdate= September 2, 2012}}</ref> He missed his rookie season with a thumb injury.  In 1998, Robinson played with the [[Rhein Fire]] of [[NFL Europe]] during the NFL the offseason. He led the NFL Europe league in receiving yards, won the season MVP award, and won the championship at [[World Bowl '98]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Isaacson|first=Melissa | url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-10-21/sports/9910210076_1_wide-receiver-marcus-robinson-bears-nfl-europe/ |date=1999-10-21 |publisher=www.chicagotribune.com |title=Robinson  Finally Catching On| accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n \nRobinson had a successful season in 1999 with the Bears, setting a team record with 1,400 receiving yards which stood until the record was broken by [[Brandon Marshall]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=McManaman|first=Bob|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/bears-28-cardinals-13-010010621--nfl.html|title=Bears 28, Cardinals 13|publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|date=2012-12-23|accessdate=2012-12-23}}</ref>\nInjuries forced him into a journeyman role for the rest of his career.\n\nAs a Baltimore Raven in 2003, Robinson caught four touchdown passes in an overtime win over the Seattle Seahawks. He was expected to be resigned, but the Ravens wanted their first star at wide receiver, so Robinson was let a free agent. He was the leading wide receiver for the Minnesota Vikings the previous three years before he was inexplicably cut on [[Christmas Eve]], 2006. The unusual move came a day after the ''[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]'' published an interview with Robinson in which he expressed displeasure with the Vikings' 6-9-1 record.<ref name=\"pinkslip\">{{cite news |author1=Siefert, Kevin |author2=Zulgad, Judd |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Vikings: Robinson gets Christmas pink slip |url=http://www.startribune.com/510/story/896547.html |format=Newspaper article |work=Minneapolis Star Tribune |date=2006-12-24 |accessdate=2006-12-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108012810/http://www.startribune.com/510/story/896547.html |archive-date=2007-01-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe signed a one-day contract with the Chicago Bears in June 2008, citing his desire to retire with the team that gave him his first chance in pro football. He officially retired on June 9, 2008.\n\n==Life after the NFL==\nRobinson is currently working as a physical trainer for young athletes, and he is the wide receiver coach for the Saint Viator football team in Arlington Heights, Illinois. He is also the sprint coach for the Marian Hurricanes track team in Woodstock, Illinois.\n\n==Personal life==\nHis nephew, [[Demarcus Robinson]], is a wide receiver in the [[NFL]] and was selected in the fourth round of the [[2016 NFL Draft]] by the [[Kansas City Chiefs]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Gators WR Demarcus Robinson says he\u2019s a new man after drug suspensions| url=http://dailydolphin.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2016/02/25/gators-wr-demarcus-robinson-says-hes-a-new-man-after-drug-suspensions/| accessdate=January 6, 2018| website=DailyDolphin.blog.PalmBeachPost.com| author=Andrew Abramson| date=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Career stats ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! Rec\n! Yds\n! TD\n|-\n| 1998\n| Chicago Bears\n| 5\n| 44\n| 1\n|-\n| 1999\n| Chicago Bears\n| 84\n| 1400\n| 9\n|-\n| 2000\n| Chicago Bears\n| 55\n| 738\n| 5\n|-\n| 2001\n| Chicago Bears\n| 23\n| 269\n| 2\n|-\n| 2002\n| Chicago Bears\n| 21\n| 244\n| 3\n|-\n| 2003\n| Baltimore Ravens\n| 31\n| 451\n| 6\n|-\n| 2004\n| Minnesota Vikings\n| 47\n| 657\n| 8\n|-\n| 2005\n| Minnesota Vikings\n| 31\n| 515\n| 5\n|-\n| 2006\n| Minnesota Vikings\n| 29\n| 381\n| 4\n|-\n|\n|\n| '''325'''\n| '''4699'''\n| '''43'''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Chicago Bears players]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n <!-- for current and future use if material is uploaded -->\n* [http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/players/4070/ SI.com: Marcus RobinsonWR#87]\n* [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/R/RobiMa00.htm Pro-Football-Reference.Com: Marcus Robinson]\n* [https://archive.is/20130203164108/http://www.startribune.com/sports/vikings/11704261.html?refer=y Star Tribune: Vikings: Robinson gets Christmas pink slip]\n\n<br/><!--this break is to put visual space between the last information and the following template if needed-->\n\n{{Bears1997DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Marcus}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Valley, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks football players]]\n[[Category:Rhein Fire players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Ravens players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Marcus Robinson\n|image=\n|position=[[Wide Receiver]]\n|number=88, 87\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1975|2|27}}\n|height_ft= 6\n|height_in= 3\n|weight_lb= 215\n|birth_place=[[Fort Valley, Georgia]]\n|high_school=[[Peach County High School|Peach County]]<br/>([[Fort Valley, Georgia]])\n|college=[[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]]\n|draftyear=1997\n|draftround=4\n|draftpick=108\n|teams=\n* [[Chicago Bears]] ([[1997 NFL season|1997]]\u2013[[2002 NFL season|2002]])\n* \u2192 [[Rhein Fire]] (1998)\n* [[Baltimore Ravens]] ([[2003 NFL season|2003]])\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ([[2004 NFL season|2004]]\u2013[[2006 NFL season|2006]])\n* [[Detroit Lions]] ([[2007 NFL season|2007]])*\n| highlights =\n* [[World Bowl VI]] (1998)\n* [[NFL Europe]] MVP (1998)\n| pastteamsnote = yes\n|statlabel1=[[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n|statvalue1=325\n|statlabel2=Receiving yards\n|statvalue2=4,699\n|statlabel3=Receiving [[touchdown]]s\n|statvalue3=43\n|nfl=ROB627446\n|pfr=R/RobiMa00\n}}\n\n'''Marcus Antonio Robinson''' (born February 27, 1975) is an [[Americans|American]] former [[American football|football]] player in the [[National Football League|NFL]], who played the position of [[wide receiver]].\n\nHe has played for the [[Chicago Bears]], the [[Baltimore Ravens]], and the [[Minnesota Vikings]], as well as the [[Rhein Fire]]. He founded the Marcus Robinson Foundation for underprivileged children.\n\n==Early life==\nRobinson was born in [[Fort Valley, Georgia|Fort Valley]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and attended Peach County High School in Fort Valley, where he starred in [[High school football|football]] and [[Track and field|track]]. In football, he won [[All-America]] and All-State honors as a [[wide receiver]], [[free safety]], and [[Punter (American football)|punter]]. In track, he won regional titles on the [[100m|100]] and [[200m|200]] meter dashes.\n\n==College career==\nRobinson played wide receiver at the [[University of South Carolina]].\n\n==Professional career==\nRobinson was drafted by the Chicago Bears in the 4th round (108th overall) of the 1997 NFL Draft.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/R/RobiMa00.htm|title= Marcus Robinson  | publisher= Pro-Football-Reference.Com |accessdate= September 2, 2012}}</ref> He missed his rookie season with a thumb injury.  In 1998, Robinson played with the [[Rhein Fire]] of [[NFL Europe]] during the NFL the offseason. He led the NFL Europe league in receiving yards, won the season MVP award, and won the championship at [[World Bowl '98]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Isaacson|first=Melissa | url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-10-21/sports/9910210076_1_wide-receiver-marcus-robinson-bears-nfl-europe/ |date=1999-10-21 |publisher=www.chicagotribune.com |title=Robinson  Finally Catching On| accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n \nRobinson had a successful season in 1999 with the Bears, setting a team record with 1,400 receiving yards which stood until the record was broken by [[Brandon Marshall]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=McManaman|first=Bob|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/bears-28-cardinals-13-010010621--nfl.html|title=Bears 28, Cardinals 13|publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|date=2012-12-23|accessdate=2012-12-23}}</ref>\nInjuries forced him into a journeyman role for the rest of his career.\n\nAs a Baltimore Raven in 2003, Robinson caught four touchdown passes in an overtime win over the Seattle Seahawks. He was expected to be resigned, but the Ravens wanted their first star at wide receiver, so Robinson was let a free agent. He was the leading wide receiver for the Minnesota Vikings the previous three years before he was inexplicably cut on [[Christmas Eve]], 2006. The unusual move came a day after the ''[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]'' published an interview with Robinson in which he expressed displeasure with the Vikings' 6-9-1 record.<ref name=\"pinkslip\">{{cite news |author1=Siefert, Kevin |author2=Zulgad, Judd |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Vikings: Robinson gets Christmas pink slip |url=http://www.startribune.com/510/story/896547.html |format=Newspaper article |work=Minneapolis Star Tribune |date=2006-12-24 |accessdate=2006-12-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108012810/http://www.startribune.com/510/story/896547.html |archive-date=2007-01-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe signed a one-day contract with the Chicago Bears in June 2008, citing his desire to retire with the team that gave him his first chance in pro football. He officially retired on June 9, 2008.\n\n==Life after the NFL==\nRobinson is currently working as a physical trainer for young athletes, and he is the wide receiver coach for the Saint Viator football team in Arlington Heights, Illinois. He is also the sprint coach for the Marian Hurricanes track team in Woodstock, Illinois.\n\n==Personal life==\nHis nephew, [[Demarcus Robinson]], is a wide receiver in the [[NFL]] and was selected in the fourth round of the [[2016 NFL Draft]] by the [[Kansas City Chiefs]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Gators WR Demarcus Robinson says he\u2019s a new man after drug suspensions| url=http://dailydolphin.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2016/02/25/gators-wr-demarcus-robinson-says-hes-a-new-man-after-drug-suspensions/| accessdate=January 6, 2018| website=DailyDolphin.blog.PalmBeachPost.com| author=Andrew Abramson| date=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Career stats ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! Rec\n! Yds\n! TD\n|-\n| 1998\n| Chicago Bears\n| 5\n| 44\n| 1\n|-\n| 1999\n| Chicago Bears\n| 84\n| 1400\n| 9\n|-\n| 2000\n| Chicago Bears\n| 55\n| 738\n| 5\n|-\n| 2001\n| Chicago Bears\n| 23\n| 269\n| 2\n|-\n| 2002\n| Chicago Bears\n| 21\n| 244\n| 3\n|-\n| 2003\n| Baltimore Ravens\n| 31\n| 451\n| 6\n|-\n| 2004\n| Minnesota Vikings\n| 47\n| 657\n| 8\n|-\n| 2005\n| Minnesota Vikings\n| 31\n| 515\n| 5\n|-\n| 2006\n| Minnesota Vikings\n| 29\n| 381\n| 4\n|-\n|\n|\n| '''325'''\n| '''4699'''\n| '''43'''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Chicago Bears players]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n <!-- for current and future use if material is uploaded -->\n* [http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/players/4070/ SI.com: Marcus RobinsonWR#87]\n* [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/R/RobiMa00.htm Pro-Football-Reference.Com: Marcus Robinson]\n* [https://archive.is/20130203164108/http://www.startribune.com/sports/vikings/11704261.html?refer=y Star Tribune: Vikings: Robinson gets Christmas pink slip]\n\n<br/><!--this break is to put visual space between the last information and the following template if needed-->\n\n{{Bears1997DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Marcus}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Valley, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks football players]]\n[[Category:Rhein Fire players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Ravens players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n", "name_user": "Rockchalk717", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marcus_Robinson_(American_football)"}
{"title_page": "Steve Harrington", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional character from the television series Stranger Things}}\n{{For|the Welsh pop singer named Steve Harrington|Steve Strange}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = #AF181F\n| image              = ST3 Steve Harrington portrait.jpg\n| caption            = [[Joe Keery]] as Steve Harrington\n| series             = [[Stranger Things]]\n| first              = \"[[Chapter One: The Vanishing of Will Byers|The Vanishing of Will Byers]]\" (2016)\n| creator            = [[The Duffer Brothers]]\n| portrayer          = [[Joe Keery]]\n| significant_other  = [[Nancy Wheeler]] (ex-girlfriend)\n| nickname           = {{Plainlist|\n* King Steve\n* Steve \"The Hair\" Harrington\n}}\n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Student at Hawkins High School\n* Former Scoops Ahoy employee\n* Family Video employee\n}}\n| children           = [[Dustin Henderson]], [[Mike Wheeler]], [[Lucas Sinclair]], [[Will Byers]], [[Max Mayfield]]\n}}\n\n'''Steve Harrington''' is a [[fictional character]] from the [[Netflix]] television show ''[[Stranger Things]]'', portrayed by [[Joe Keery]]. While starting out as a typical jock character, Steve has grown into a more paternal and caring character as the show has progressed, a development that has received widespread acclaim from critics and fans alike and has led to Steve becoming one of the show\u2019s most beloved and enduring characters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/07/stranger-things-3-steve-harrington-actor-joe-keery-interview|title= An Ode to Steve Harrington, the soft hero Stranger Things fans deserve|date=2019-07-04|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> Initially a part of the recurring cast, Joe Keery was promoted to the main cast in the second season. Steve is a side antagonist turned protagonist of [[Stranger Things (season 1)|season 1]], and one of the main protagonists of [[Stranger Things (season 2)|season 2]] and [[Stranger Things (season 3)|season 3]].\n\n==Fictional character biography==\n\n===Season 1===\n{{See also|Stranger Things (season 1)}}\nSteve is initially portrayed as a stereotypical 1980s jock character, antagonistic and unlikable. Steve had been dating [[Nancy Wheeler]] but after he harasses [[List of Stranger Things characters#Jonathan Byers|Jonathan Byers]] by breaking his camera, Nancy seems to become close to Jonathan. Steve accosts Jonathan, but Jonathan beats him in a fight and Steve sees the error of his ways. Traveling to the Byers' home to apologize, he becomes involved in Nancy and Jonathan's fight against the Demogorgon, which they defeat. At the conclusion of the season, Nancy buys Jonathan a new camera and Steve continues his relationship with Nancy.\n\n===Season 2===\n{{See also|Stranger Things (season 2)}}\nSteve's relationship with Nancy is stressed, and he breaks up with her after she will not say she loves him. He calls her out after her drunken tirade at a party where she calls their relationship fake. Steve also finds himself at odds with [[List of Stranger Things characters#Billy Hargrove|Billy Hargrove]], a new student at the school who seeks to become its tough guy. Steve becomes involved with [[Mike Wheeler (Stranger Things)|Mike Wheeler]] and his friends after [[Dustin Henderson|Dustin]] asks him to help find his \"pet\" D'Artagnan, unaware it is a Demogorgon. Steve and Dustin bond over how to talk to girls, and soon Steve takes Mike, Lucas, and Billy's stepsister [[List of Stranger Things characters#Max Mayfield|Max]] under his wing. Steve protects the children as Demodogs start ravaging across Hawkins, giving time for [[Eleven (Stranger Things)|Eleven]] and [[Jim Hopper (Stranger Things)|Jim Hopper]] to close the gate to the Upside Down, and for Will Byers to have the Mind Flayer exorcised from his body.\n\n===Season 3===\n{{See also|Stranger Things (season 3)}}\nNow graduated from high school, Steve works at the Scoops Ahoy! ice cream parlor at Starcourt Mall with Robin Buckley ([[Maya Hawke]]), a former classmate who teases him frequently. Dustin, having returned from science camp and set up a [[ham radio]] tower to talk with his new girlfriend Suzie in Utah, gets Steve's help to translate a Russian radio message he overheard. Robin helps with the translation, indicating a site at the mall, and Lucas' sister Erica (Priah Ferguson) is recruited to sneak into the site in exchange for free ice cream. Steve, Robin, Dustin, and Erica find a secret Russian base under the mall that is attempting to open a portal to the Upside Down. Though Steve and Robin are captured and drugged, Dustin and Erica help save them and return to the surface to warn the others. Whilst coming down off the drugs, Steve admits he is attracted to Robin and learns that Robin is a lesbian, yet accepts her sexuality. In the following battle with the Mind Flayer, Steve helps to stop the possessed Billy from ramming the car that the others are using to escort Eleven away, and joins the rest in distracting the Mind Flayer with fireworks as the gate in the Russian base is shut down. With the mall's destruction from the battle, Steve and Robin lose their jobs at Scoops Ahoy! and get work at the local [[Family Video]].\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe character appears in ''[[Dead by Daylight]]'' as a DLC character along with [[Nancy Wheeler]] as a fellow survivor being hunted by the Demogorgon throughout the Hawkins Lab.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/19/20812070/stranger-things-dead-by-daylight-nancy-wheeler-steve-harrington-demogorgon-chapter |title= ''Stranger Things'' is coming to ''Dead by Daylight'' in a new update |date=2019-08-19 |website=Polygon |language=en |access-date=2019-08-31}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe character development of Steve Harrington in the [[Stranger Things 2|second season of the show]] has been met with acclaim and has led to Steve becoming a fan-favorite character and critical darling on the show, and Joe Keery received critical acclaim for his performance. The transition from stereotypical bully and lothario to a caring and protective character was lauded by critics and audiences. Fans, in particular, enjoyed his budding friendship with [[Dustin Henderson]] and the protective way he began looking after the kids, which has led to many fans referring to him as \"Mom Steve\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/stranger-things-how-steve-harrington-became-season-2s-breakout-hero-1053901|title='Stranger Things' How Steve Harrington Became Season 2's Breakout Hero|date=2017-11-01|website=Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n \nThe progression of the character continued in [[Stranger Things 3|the third season]] with the introduction of his co-worker [[List of Stranger Things characters#Robin Buckley|Robin Buckley]]. The chemistry between actors Joe Keery and [[Maya Hawke]] was critically acclaimed, as was the development of a new comedic side to Steve's character. In particular, Steve's positive reaction to Robin's [[coming out]] as a lesbian has been praised for its thoughtful and understanding nature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a28352776/stranger-things-3-steve-harrington-joe-keery/|title=Stranger Things knew Steve Harrington was {{sic|it's|nolink=y}} best character, then it made him even better|date=2019-07-10|website=Men\u2019s Health|language=en|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Stranger Things}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrington, Steve}}\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2016]]\n[[Category:Stranger Things characters]]\n[[Category:Dead by Daylight characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Fictional bullies]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of bullies]]\n[[Category:Horror television characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional character from the television series Stranger Things}}\n{{For|the Welsh pop singer named Steve Harrington|Steve Strange}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = #AF181F\n| image              = ST3 Steve Harrington portrait.jpg\n| caption            = [[Joe Keery]] as Steve Harrington\n| series             = [[Stranger Things]]\n| first              = \"[[Chapter One: The Vanishing of Will Byers|The Vanishing of Will Byers]]\" (2016)\n| creator            = [[The Duffer Brothers]]\n| portrayer          = [[Joe Keery]]\n| significant_other  = [[Nancy Wheeler]] (ex-girlfriend)\n| nickname           = {{Plainlist|\n* King Steve\n* Steve \"The Hair\" Harrington\n}}\n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Student at Hawkins High School\n* Former Scoops Ahoy employee\n* Family Video employee\n}}\n| children           = [[Dustin Henderson]],[[Mike Wheeler]],[[Lucas Sinclair]],[[Will Byers]],[[Max Mayfield]]\n}}\n\n'''Steve Harrington''' is a [[fictional character]] from the [[Netflix]] television show ''[[Stranger Things]]'', portrayed by [[Joe Keery]]. While starting out as a typical jock character, Steve has grown into a more paternal and caring character as the show has progressed, a development that has received widespread acclaim from critics and fans alike and has led to Steve becoming one of the show\u2019s most beloved and enduring characters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/07/stranger-things-3-steve-harrington-actor-joe-keery-interview|title= An Ode to Steve Harrington, the soft hero Stranger Things fans deserve|date=2019-07-04|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> Initially a part of the recurring cast, Joe Keery was promoted to the main cast in the second season. Steve is a side antagonist turned protagonist of [[Stranger Things (season 1)|season 1]], and one of the main protagonists of [[Stranger Things (season 2)|season 2]] and [[Stranger Things (season 3)|season 3]].\n\n==Fictional character biography==\n\n===Season 1===\n{{See also|Stranger Things (season 1)}}\nSteve is initially portrayed as a stereotypical 1980s jock character, antagonistic and unlikable. Steve had been dating [[Nancy Wheeler]] but after he harasses [[List of Stranger Things characters#Jonathan Byers|Jonathan Byers]] by breaking his camera, Nancy seems to become close to Jonathan. Steve accosts Jonathan, but Jonathan beats him in a fight and Steve sees the error of his ways. Traveling to the Byers' home to apologize, he becomes involved in Nancy and Jonathan's fight against the Demogorgon, which they defeat. At the conclusion of the season, Nancy buys Jonathan a new camera and Steve continues his relationship with Nancy.\n\n===Season 2===\n{{See also|Stranger Things (season 2)}}\nSteve's relationship with Nancy is stressed, and he breaks up with her after she will not say she loves him. He calls her out after her drunken tirade at a party where she calls their relationship fake. Steve also finds himself at odds with [[List of Stranger Things characters#Billy Hargrove|Billy Hargrove]], a new student at the school who seeks to become its tough guy. Steve becomes involved with [[Mike Wheeler (Stranger Things)|Mike Wheeler]] and his friends after [[Dustin Henderson|Dustin]] asks him to help find his \"pet\" D'Artagnan, unaware it is a Demogorgon. Steve and Dustin bond over how to talk to girls, and soon Steve takes Mike, Lucas, and Billy's stepsister [[List of Stranger Things characters#Max Mayfield|Max]] under his wing. Steve protects the children as Demodogs start ravaging across Hawkins, giving time for [[Eleven (Stranger Things)|Eleven]] and [[Jim Hopper (Stranger Things)|Jim Hopper]] to close the gate to the Upside Down, and for Will Byers to have the Mind Flayer exorcised from his body.\n\n===Season 3===\n{{See also|Stranger Things (season 3)}}\nNow graduated from high school, Steve works at the Scoops Ahoy! ice cream parlor at Starcourt Mall with Robin Buckley ([[Maya Hawke]]), a former classmate who teases him frequently. Dustin, having returned from science camp and set up a [[ham radio]] tower to talk with his new girlfriend Suzie in Utah, gets Steve's help to translate a Russian radio message he overheard. Robin helps with the translation, indicating a site at the mall, and Lucas' sister Erica (Priah Ferguson) is recruited to sneak into the site in exchange for free ice cream. Steve, Robin, Dustin, and Erica find a secret Russian base under the mall that is attempting to open a portal to the Upside Down. Though Steve and Robin are captured and drugged, Dustin and Erica help save them and return to the surface to warn the others. Whilst coming down off the drugs, Steve admits he is attracted to Robin and learns that Robin is a lesbian, yet accepts her sexuality. In the following battle with the Mind Flayer, Steve helps to stop the possessed Billy from ramming the car that the others are using to escort Eleven away, and joins the rest in distracting the Mind Flayer with fireworks as the gate in the Russian base is shut down. With the mall's destruction from the battle, Steve and Robin lose their jobs at Scoops Ahoy! and get work at the local [[Family Video]].\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe character appears in ''[[Dead by Daylight]]'' as a DLC character along with [[Nancy Wheeler]] as a fellow survivor being hunted by the Demogorgon throughout the Hawkins Lab.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/19/20812070/stranger-things-dead-by-daylight-nancy-wheeler-steve-harrington-demogorgon-chapter |title= ''Stranger Things'' is coming to ''Dead by Daylight'' in a new update |date=2019-08-19 |website=Polygon |language=en |access-date=2019-08-31}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe character development of Steve Harrington in the [[Stranger Things 2|second season of the show]] has been met with acclaim and has led to Steve becoming a fan-favorite character and critical darling on the show, and Joe Keery received critical acclaim for his performance. The transition from stereotypical bully and lothario to a caring and protective character was lauded by critics and audiences. Fans, in particular, enjoyed his budding friendship with [[Dustin Henderson]] and the protective way he began looking after the kids, which has led to many fans referring to him as \"Mom Steve\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/stranger-things-how-steve-harrington-became-season-2s-breakout-hero-1053901|title='Stranger Things' How Steve Harrington Became Season 2's Breakout Hero|date=2017-11-01|website=Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n \nThe progression of the character continued in [[Stranger Things 3|the third season]] with the introduction of his co-worker [[List of Stranger Things characters#Robin Buckley|Robin Buckley]]. The chemistry between actors Joe Keery and [[Maya Hawke]] was critically acclaimed, as was the development of a new comedic side to Steve's character. In particular, Steve's positive reaction to Robin's [[coming out]] as a lesbian has been praised for its thoughtful and understanding nature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a28352776/stranger-things-3-steve-harrington-joe-keery/|title=Stranger Things knew Steve Harrington was {{sic|it's|nolink=y}} best character, then it made him even better|date=2019-07-10|website=Men\u2019s Health|language=en|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Stranger Things}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrington, Steve}}\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2016]]\n[[Category:Stranger Things characters]]\n[[Category:Dead by Daylight characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Fictional bullies]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of bullies]]\n[[Category:Horror television characters]]\n", "name_user": "CharlieRS", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Harrington"}
{"title_page": "Family Guy (season 18)", "text_new": "{{short description|Season of American animated sitcom television series Family Guy}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number = 18\n| bgcolor       = #99FF00\n| image         = familyguys18cover.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.14\n| image_alt     = \n| caption       = Digital purchase image\n| country       = United States\n| num_episodes  = 15\n| network       = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| first_aired   = {{Start date|2019|9|29}}\n| last_aired    = present\n| episode_list  = List of Family Guy episodes\n}}\n''[[Family Guy]]''{{'s}} eighteenth season was announced on February 12, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|author= Holywoodreporter|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/family-guy-bobs-burgers-renewed-at-fox-1186030 |title=Season 18 Renewal|publisher=Hollywoodreporter |date=February 12, 2019 |accessdate=2019-02-12}}</ref> It premiered on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] on September 29, 2019.\n\nThe series follows the dysfunctional [[Griffin family]], consisting of father [[Peter Griffin|Peter]], mother [[Lois Griffin|Lois]], daughter [[Meg Griffin|Meg]], son [[Chris Griffin|Chris]], baby [[Stewie Griffin|Stewie]], and the family dog [[Brian Griffin|Brian]], who reside in their hometown of Quahog. The season includes a crossover with ''[[Beavis and Butt-Head]]'' guest starring [[Mike Judge]] reprising his roles as [[Beavis]] and [[Butt-Head]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Family Guy season 18 first-look trailer reveals Beavis and Butt-Head crossover|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a28460157/family-guy-season-18-trailer-beavis-and-butt-head-crossover/|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe season's executive producers are [[Seth MacFarlane]], [[Alec Sulkin]], [[Richard Appel]], [[Steve Callaghan]], [[Danny Smith (writer)|Danny Smith]], [[Kara Vallow]], [[Mark Hentemann]], [[Tom Devanney]], [[Patrick Meighan (writer)|Patrick Meighan]] and [[Cherry Chevapravatdumrong]]. The season's showrunners are Sulkin and Appel.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{see also|List of Family Guy episodes}}\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:Episode table|main\n|background = #99FF00\n|overall    = \n|season     = \n|title      = \n|titleR     = <ref name=\"TFC\"/>\n|director   = \n|writer     = \n|airdate    = \n|airdateR   = <ref name=\"TFC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/family-guy/listings/|title=Family Guy on Fox|accessdate=October 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|prodcode   = \n|viewers    = \n|country    = U.S.\n|episodes   = \n{{Episode list/sublist|Family Guy (season 18)\n |EpisodeNumber= 330\n |EpisodeNumber2= 1\n |Title= Yacht Rocky\n |DirectedBy= [[John Holmquist]]\n |WrittenBy= Travis Bowe\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2019|9|29}}\n |ProdCode= HACX18\n |Viewers= 1.88<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-final-ratings-sept-29-2019/|title='60 Minutes,' 'NCIS: Los Angeles,' and 'Sunday Night Football' adjust up: Sunday final ratings|last=Welch|first=Alex|work=TV by the Numbers|date=October 1, 2019|accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary= Peter's job announces that due to cutbacks they need to let one male employee go. When the final choice comes down to Peter and another employee, Peter blacks out from the stress. After he awakens in the hospital, Dr. Hartman connects him with a \"[[yacht rock]]\" music collection to help him relax. When the guys get hooked on the music as well, they learn of an upcoming Yacht Rock Cruise and decide to all go along. While attempting to board, Brian finds himself in a dog crate and stored beneath deck. On board, the rest of the family and Peter's friends rub shoulders with numerous stars. But when the ship's captain gets distracted hanging out with Peter, he leaves the bridge unattended as a rogue wave capsizes the ship. Struggling to survive, everyone has to make their way towards the bottom of the ship where the hull is the thinnest. When they finally reach their goal and meet up with Brian in the process, they realize that they have no tools to cut through the hull. Turning fearful as the water rises, the episode is resolved by simply cutting to everybody safe back at home.\n----\nNote: This episode is a parody of the film ''[[The Poseidon Adventure (1972 film)|The Poseidon Adventure]]''.\n |LineColor=#99FF00\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Family Guy (season 18)\n |EpisodeNumber= 331\n |EpisodeNumber2= 2\n |Title= Bri-Da\n |DirectedBy= Steve Robertson\n |WrittenBy= [[Tom Devanney]]\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2019|10|6}}\n |ProdCode= HACX19\n |Viewers= 2.31<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-final-ratings-oct-6-2019/|title='Sunday Night Football' adjusts up, 'The Simpsons,' 'Bless the Harts,' and others adjust down: Sunday final ratings|last=Welch|first=Alex|work=TV by the Numbers|date=October 8, 2019|accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary= Hungover after a night out, Peter, Joe, Quagmire and Cleveland realise they had a brilliant, million-dollar ideas but have no clue what it was. To make sure they don't lose any more million-dollar ideas while they're drunk, they all fit themselves with police-grade body cams. Reviewing the footage following another night out shows Peter, Joe and Cleveland pitching an idea on [[Shark Tank]], whilst Quagmire is in bed with a random woman, but he is shocked when Joe reveals that all the footage from the cameras is already online. Meanwhile, Brian finds Quagmire's transgender mother, Ida, in a hotel bar after shes seen the video, and the two end up spending the night together again, except this time they both decide to enter a relationship together which Quagmire vehemently objects to. Despite Brians efforts to show his seriousness and bond with him, Quagmire forces Ida to choose between either Himself or in her life. Ida chooses her son, so she and Brian decide to end their relationship amicably, with fond memories of their time together.\n |LineColor=#99FF00\n}}\n{