ble News Stations|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-over-12-million-watch-impeachment-vote-coverage-across-various-cable-news-stations/|website=Programming Insider|access-date=March 27, 2020|date=December 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328034025/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-over-12-million-watch-impeachment-vote-coverage-across-various-cable-news-stations/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2019\u201320 United States network television schedule|2019\u201320]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBA}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBA}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBA}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBA}}\n|-\n| [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|3]]\n| {{n/a|TBA}}\n| February 2, 2020\n| 23.78<ref>{{cite web|url=https://programminginsider.com/sunday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-third-season-premiere-on-fox-generates-second-largest-total-audience-and-adults-18-49-delivery-for-a-super-bowl-lead-out-in-five-years/|title=Sunday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' Third Season Premiere on Fox Generates Second-Largest Total Audience and Adults 18-49 Delivery for a Super Bowl Lead-Out in Five Years|work=Programming Insider|author=Douglas Pucci|date=February 11, 2020|access-date=February 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211224755/https://programminginsider.com/sunday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-third-season-premiere-on-fox-generates-second-largest-total-audience-and-adults-18-49-delivery-for-a-super-bowl-lead-out-in-five-years/|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| May 27, 2020<ref name=\"TFC Listings\"/>\n| {{n/a|TBA}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Spin-offs==\n===''The Masked Singer: After the Mask''===\n\nOn April 8, 2020, Fox announced that Nick Cannon will host an [[aftershow]] of the series titled ''The Masked Singer: After the Mask'' on Wednesdays at 9:00 p.m. for four weeks starting on April 22. He will host the show from his house and discuss the outcome of the preceding episode. The show will also feature remote appearances of celebrity guests as well as games and musical performances.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=''The Masked Singer'' After-Show, Hosted by Nick Cannon, to Launch on Fox|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/the-masked-singer-after-the-mask-nick-cannon-fox-1234574761/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 8, 2020|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Roots|first=Kimberly|title=''The Masked Singer'' to Get Aftershow|url=https://tvline.com/2020/04/08/the-masked-singer-aftershow-nick-cannon-season-3-fox/|website=[[TVLine]]|date=April 8, 2020|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''The Masked Dancer''===\nOn {{nobr|January 7, 2020,}} at the winter [[Television Critics Association]] press tour, Fox Alternative Entertainment and [[Warner Bros. Television]] announced that they had ordered a spin-off series, ''The Masked Dancer'', with [[Ellen DeGeneres]] as executive producer. DeGeneres had previously conducted ''The Masked Dancer'' as a recurring segment of her syndicated [[talk show]] ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', as a {{nobr|self-admitted}} parody of ''The Masked Singer''. DeGeneres stated that the show was \"gonna be just as fun and suspenseful\", but \"with a lot more [[krumping]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/the-masked-dancer-fox-partners-with-ellen-degeneres-on-the-masked-singer-spin-off-1202823169/|title=\u2018The Masked Dancer\u2019: Fox Partners With Ellen DeGeneres On \u2018The Masked Singer\u2019 Spinoff \u2013 TCA|last=White|first=Peter|last2=White|first2=Peter|date=January 7, 2020|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/pug-almost-passes-out-playing-ellen-degeneres-latest-masked-singer-ripoff-video/|title=A Pug Almost Passes Out Playing Ellen DeGeneres' Latest 'Masked Dancer'|date=February 18, 2019|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===National Tour===\nOn {{nobr|February 12, 2020,}} it was announced that the show would be getting a live national tour with shows in over forty-five cities. Beginning at the [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]] on {{nobr|May 28, 2020}}, the tour will feature two celebrity hosts as well as a local mystery celebrity who is unmasked at the end of each show.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20200212005953/en/MASKED-SINGER-Unveils-45-City-U.S.-National|title=THE MASKED SINGER Unveils 45+ City U.S. National Tour|via=[[Business Wire]]|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018The Masked Singer\u2019 Announces Nationwide Concert Tour This Summer|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/masked-singer-concert-tour-summer-1203502739/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Michael Schneider|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasts==\nThe series is broadcast by Fox in the United States and is [[simulcast]] by [[CTV Television Network|CTV]] in Canada since the second season. The show is available for streaming in the United States on Fox's website and [[Hulu]], and in Canada on CTV's website.<ref>{{cite press release|title= CTV Unveils 2019/20 Primetime Schedule, Featuring Dynamic Dramas with Big Stars and Big Stories|url=https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|publisher=[[Bell Media]]|access-date=April 5, 2020|date=June 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607044629/https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|archive-date=June 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Watch The Masked Singer|url=https://www.hulu.com/series/the-masked-singer-15209f88-6004-4d73-b993-3ff1a244f494|publisher=[[Hulu]]|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{sequence\n|prev=''[[The World's Best ]]''<br />[[Super Bowl LIII|2019]]\n|list=[[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|Super Bowl lead-out program]]<br />''The Masked Singer''<br />[[Super Bowl LIV|2020]]\n|next=TBA\n}}\n\n{{The Masked Singer (American TV series)}}\n{{Masked Singer series}}\n{{FOXNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masked Singer, The}}\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Fox Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:2010s American music television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2020s American music television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American game shows]]\n[[Category:American television series based on South Korean television series]]\n[[Category:Music competitions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl lead-out programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by Endemol]]\n[[Category:Television series by Fox Entertainment]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the current season|The Masked Singer (American season 3)}}\n{{short description|American reality singing competition television show}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name      = The Masked Singer\n| image          = File:Masked Singer USA Logo.png\n| image_alt      = Title card of ''The Masked Singer''\n| caption        = \n| genre          = [[Reality competition]]<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\">{{cite web|last=Piester|first=Lauren|title= The Secrets of ''The Masked Singer'': Everything We've Learned About TV's Most Mysterious Show |url=https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/1019279/the-secrets-of-the-masked-singer-everything-we-ve-learned-about-tv-s-most-mysterious-show|date=February 27, 2019|access-date=April 5, 2020|website=[[E!#E! Online|E!]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703044452/https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/1019279/the-secrets-of-the-masked-singer-everything-we-ve-learned-about-tv-s-most-mysterious-show|archive-date=July 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| creator        = \n| based_on       = {{based_on|''[[King of Mask Singer]]''|[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]]}}\n| developer      = [[Craig Plestis]]\n| director       = {{unbulleted list|Alex Rudzinski|Brad Duns}}\n| presenter      = [[Nick Cannon]]\n| starring       = {{unbulleted list|[[Ken Jeong]]|[[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]|[[Nicole Scherzinger]]|[[Robin Thicke]]}}\n| narrated       = \n| composer       = \n| executive_producer = {{unbulleted list|Craig Plestis ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1\u2013)|Izzie Pick Ibarra ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1\u2013)|Rosie Seitchik ({{abbr|s.|season}} 2\u2013)|Nick Cannon ({{abbr|s.|season}} 3\u2013)}}\n| producer       = \n| company        = {{unbulleted list|Smart Dog Media|[[Endemol Shine North America]] ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1)|Fox Alternative Entertainment ({{abbr|s.|season}} 2\u2013)}}\n| distributor    = {{unbulleted list|[[Fox Corporation]]{{efn|[[Fox Corporation]] distributes the series in the United States and Canada.}}|Propagate Content{{efn|Propagate Content distributes the series outside of the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite web|last=Otterson|first=Joe|title=Fox Partners With Propagate Content to Distribute Unscripted Programming |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/fox-propagate-content-mipcom-1203372433/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017154840/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/fox-propagate-content-mipcom-1203372433/|archivedate=October 17, 2019|date=October 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}}}}\n| location       = \n| camera         = \n| runtime        = 42\u201385 minutes\n| opentheme      = {{theme_song|\"[[Who Are You (The Who song)|Who Are You]]\"|[[The Who]]}}\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| network        = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| channel        = \n| picture_format = \n| audio_format   = \n| first_run      = \n| released       = \n| first_aired    = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| last_aired     = present\n| num_seasons    = 3\n| num_episodes   = 34<!-- as of April 1, 2020 -->\n| list_episodes  = List of The Masked Singer (American TV series) episodes\n| preceded_by    = \n| related        = ''The Masked Dancer''\n| website        = https://www.fox.com/the-masked-singer/\n| production_website = https://www.smartdogmedia.com/the-masked-singer\n}}\n\n'''''The Masked Singer''''' is an American [[Reality competition|reality singing competition]] television series, part of the ''[[Masked Singer]]'' franchise, featuring celebrities in head-to-toe costumes and face masks which conceal their identities from other contestants, panelists, and an audience. The series premiered on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] on {{nobr|January 2, 2019,}} and is hosted by [[Nick Cannon]].\n\nThe series is currently in its [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|third season]] which premiered [[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|after]] [[Super Bowl LIV]] on {{nobr|February 2, 2020.}} In an interview prior to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Rob Wade, President of Alternative Entertainment and Specials at Fox, confirmed that future seasons of the show are planned.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 6\">{{cite web|last=Daswani|first=Mansha|title=Fox Entertainment's Rob Wade|url=https://worldscreen.com/tvformats/fox-entertainments-rob-wade/|website=TV Formats|access-date=April 8, 2020|date=April 6, 2019|quote=And then ''The Masked Dancer'' is coming up soon. And future cycles of ''The Masked Singer.''}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{Listen|pos=left|filename=Masked Singer US Monster Voiceover.ogg|title=Monster voiceover|description=A sample of a typical voiceover in a clue package showing how modulation is used to disguise the actual identity of the performers on the show while they give hints about their backgrounds.|format=[[Ogg]]}}\nA group of [[Celebrity|celebrities]] compete on the show anonymously in costumes over a series of episodes. The specific format of the competition varies by season and episode, depending on how many celebrities remain, but generally, each episode features four to six celebrities performing a cover of a famous song, with the audience voting for their favorite. The celebrity with the fewest votes in that episode is eliminated from the competition and must take off their mask and reveal their identity.<ref name=\"PeopleS3\">{{cite web|last=Stone|first=Natalie|title=The Masked Singer Renewed for Season 3, to Premiere After 2020 Super Bowl|url=https://people.com/tv/the-masked-singer-renewed-for-season-3/|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|access-date=May 13, 2019|date=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the singing competition, hints to each masked singer's identity are offered during the show, referred to as the \"clue package\" by the panelists. Such clues may feature cryptic allusions to what the celebrity is known for, or may be more direct references. Pre-taped interviews are given as hints and feature celebrities' electronically masked voices. The panelists are given time to speculate the identity of the singer after the performance, including the opportunity to ask questions or gain additional clues offered by the host.<ref name=\"PeopleS3\"/>\n\n==Panelists and host==\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 450\n| total_height\n| align = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1   = Ken Jeong March 2015.jpg\n| alt1     = Ken Jeong\n| caption1 = [[Ken Jeong]]\n| image2   = Jenny McCarthy at E3 2006.jpg\n| alt2     = Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg\n| caption2 = [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]\n| image3   = Nicole Scherzinger 2012.jpg\n| alt3     = Nicole Scherzinger\n| caption3 = [[Nicole Scherzinger]]\n| image4   = Robin Thicke 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| alt4     = Robin Thicke\n| caption4 = [[Robin Thicke]]\n| image5   = Nick Cannon by David Shankbone.jpg\n| alt5     = Nick Cannon\n| caption5 = [[Nick Cannon]] \n}}\n\nSince the first season, the permanent panel has consisted of actor and comedian [[Ken Jeong]], television personality [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]], recording artist [[Nicole Scherzinger]], and singer-songwriter [[Robin Thicke]], with [[Nick Cannon]] hosting the show.<ref name=\"VAR Aug 2\">{{cite web|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|title=Fox Orders ''Masked Singer'' Reality Series; Nick Cannon to Host|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/fox-masked-singer-reality-series-nick-cannon-1202893337/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102132907/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/fox-masked-singer-reality-series-nick-cannon-1202893337/|archive-date=November 2, 2019|date=August 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThere are often guest panelists that appear as the fifth panelist on the series, occasionally for multiple episodes. In the first season, they were comedian [[Joel McHale]] {{nobr|(episodes 3\u20134),}} actor [[J. B. Smoove]] {{nobr|(episode 7),}} and actor and comedian [[Kenan Thompson]] {{nobr|(episodes 8 and 10).}} In the second season, they were [[Anthony Anderson]] {{nobr|(episode 6),}} [[Triumph the Insult Comic Dog]] (Robert Smigel; {{nobr|episode 7),}} McHale {{nobr|(episodes 8-9),}} and the winner of the first season, [[T-Pain]] {{nobr|(episode 10).}} In the third season, the guest panelists included [[Jamie Foxx]] {{nobr|(episode 1),}} [[Jason Biggs]] {{nobr|(episode 2),}} [[Leah Remini]] {{nobr|(episode 3),}} [[Gabriel Iglesias]] {{nobr|(episode 5),}} T-Pain {{nobr|(episode 6),}} McHale {{nobr|(episode 8),}} and [[Will Arnett]] {{nobr|(episode 9),}} with [[Yvette Nicole Brown]] set to appear in the eleventh episode,<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-312) \"The Mother Of All Final Face Offs, Part 1\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200403fox02/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> [[Sharon Osbourne]] in the twelfth,<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-313) \"The Mother Of All Final Face Offs, Part 2\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200402fox05/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> and [[Gordon Ramsay]] in the thirteenth.<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-314) \"The Battle of The Sixes: The Final 6\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200408fox06/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size:90%; width:30%;\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\"| Panelist timeline\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15%;\"| Panelists\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"width:15%;\"| Seasons\n|-\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|1]]\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|2]]\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|3]]\n|-\n| [[Ken Jeong]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Nicole Scherzinger]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Robin Thicke]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Joel McHale]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[J.B. Smoove]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Kenan Thompson]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Anthony Anderson]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Triumph the Comic Insult Dog]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[T-Pain]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jamie Foxx]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jason Biggs]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Leah Remini]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Gabriel Iglesias]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Will Arnett]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Yvette Nicole Brown]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Sharon Osbourne]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Gordon Ramsay]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|}\n\n==Production==\n===Conception and development===\n{{quote box|quote=So we're at a restaurant and my back is to the TV. My daughter said Dad, look at this, there's this crazy thing on. I turned around and all the diners were watching the TV screen. I saw a kangaroo in black pleather singing a pop song. At that moment I said, oh my gosh, I love this! It was bizarre. It was flypaper. It was in a foreign language and you didn't know what was going on, and it was still working. I found out that it was a hit format in Korea, it was a hit show in Thailand. And no one had the [U.S.] rights.|source=\u2014Plestis on the creation of ''The Masked Singer''<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/>|align=right|width=35em}}\n\n''The Masked Singer'' is based on the South Korean series ''[[King of Mask Singer]]''. Television producer [[Craig Plestis]] explained that he first discovered the format during a visit to a small [[Los Angeles]] Thai restaurant in October 2017. While waiting for dinner, he observed that the other patrons were all staring at a television while an episode of the [[The Mask Singer (Thai TV series)|Thai version]] of the show was playing. Intrigued, Plestis began to research the series and secured the rights to produce an American adaptation within one week in a deal brokered by Steve Wohl of [[Paradigm Talent Agency]]. Plestis then called Fox executive Rob Wade on a Friday night telling him he needed to come in the following Monday and worked to create a showcase during the weekend. After successfully pitching the show, the series began development in November,<ref name=\"THR Jan 2\">{{cite web|last=Bentley|first=Jean|title=''The Masked Singer'': How the Fox Reality Show Scored Top Talent (and Kept It Secret)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/masked-singer-ep-explains-how-his-insane-reality-competition-made-it-air-1171775|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=April 8, 2020|date=January 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713155810/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/masked-singer-ep-explains-how-his-insane-reality-competition-made-it-air-1171775|archive-date=July 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=Peter|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/fox-remaking-asian-singing-contest-the-masked-singer-1202206986/|title=Fox Developing Remake of Asian Talent Competition \u2018The Masked Singer\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 13, 2017|access-date=April 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521062138/https://deadline.com/2017/11/fox-remaking-asian-singing-contest-the-masked-singer-1202206986/|archive-date=May 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\">{{cite web|last=Ravindran|first=Manori|title=How ''Masked Singer'' is reviving costume-led formats|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/04/05/costume-drama/|website=Television Business International|access-date=April 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407120916/https://tbivision.com/2019/04/05/costume-drama/|archive-date=April 7, 2019|date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\">{{cite magazine|last=Daswani|first=Mansha|title=Craig Plestis|url=https://issuu.com/worldscreen/docs/tv_formats_miptv_2019|page=38|work=TV Formats|access-date=April 8, 2020|date=April 2019|via=[[Issuu]]}}</ref> and was officially ordered by Fox in August 2018.<ref name=\"VAR Aug 2\"/>\n\nDue to Plestis' relationship with the studio, the [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|first season]] of ''The Masked Singer'' was produced by [[Endemol Shine North America]], then-owned partly by Fox's parent company [[21st Century Fox]] (the stake is now owned by [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]). For the second season, production transitioned to a new in-house studio, Fox Alternative Entertainment, and the show's budget was lowered as a result.<ref>{{cite web|last=Haynes|first=Dade|title=''The Masked Singer'' Renewed For Third Season, Gets Post-Super Bowl Slot On|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-masked-singer-season-3-to-premiere-after-super-bowl-liv-on-fox-1202613462/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=May 13, 2019|date=May 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-launching-unscripted-studio-masked-singer-1209087|title=Fox Launching Unscripted Studio With ''The Masked Singer'' (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> Wade said this gave the network further creative control over the show and allowed it to sell merchandise, launch a national tour, and create spin-off series ''The Masked Dancer''.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 6\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nExecutive producer Izzie Pick Ibarra was ecstatic when Nick Cannon agreed to host the show, citing him as her number-one choice for the role because of his personality and experience. Regarding the panelists, she said the production team was less concerned with selecting those with an ability to critique participants' singing abilities than panelists who could create a comedic tone for the show; one of their goals was to reassure celebrities they would not be ridiculed for choosing to appear. Jeong was the first panelist to be signed on to the series due to his humour and pre-existing knowledge of the South Korean version, followed by McCarthy Wahlberg, Thicke, and Scherzinger.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> On {{nobr|March 28, 2019,}} Osbourne revealed on ''[[The Talk (talk show)|The Talk]]'' that she was originally supposed to be signed on as a panelist for the series; those plans fell through after being contractually obligated to appear on ''[[The X Factor (British TV series)|The X Factor]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Furdyk|first=Brent|url=https://etcanada.com/news/435743/sharon-osbourne-shreds-simon-cowell-for-firing-her-from-the-x-factor-because-he-thought-i-was-too-old/|title=Sharon Osbourne Shreds Simon Cowell For Firing Her From ''The X Factor'' Because He \"Thought I Was Too Old\"|website=[[Entertainment Tonight Canada|ET Canada]]|date=March 28, 2019|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330152540/https://etcanada.com/news/435743/sharon-osbourne-shreds-simon-cowell-for-firing-her-from-the-x-factor-because-he-thought-i-was-too-old/|archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIbarra described casting for the series' first season as less difficult than she predicted due to her strategy of sending the possible participants sketches of costumes that might be featured on the series. She said many of the celebrities had emotional reactions when presented with the proposed costumes and that they were excited about using the show as a way of reinventing their [[reputation|public image]]. [[T-Pain]], the winner of the first season, said he was skeptical about the series until he saw the costume choices, citing the opportunity to wear the Monster outfit as his motivation for participating in the show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jensen|first=Erin|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/03/22/t-pain-masked-singer-winner-pitch/3244569002/|title=''Masked Singer'' winner T-Pain first deemed show \"probably the stupidest thing\" he'd heard|website=[[USA Today]]|date=March 22, 2019|access-date=April 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111040704/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/03/22/t-pain-masked-singer-winner-pitch/3244569002/|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Conversely, [[Wayne Brady]], the winner of the second season, was approached by producers to appear in the first season but turned them down after being confused about the show's concept.<ref name=\"VAR Dec 18\">{{cite web|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady-the-fox-season-2-1203447936/|title=''The Masked Singer'' Winner Interview: \"It\u2019s the First Time in My Life I Kept a Secret Months on End\"|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 18, 2019|access-date=April 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110134353/https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady-the-fox-season-2-1203447936/|archive-date=January 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Those who are not professional singers send the show's production crew clips of them singing as a quasi-audition before participating in the series.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\">{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8549443/masked-singer-showrunner-season-3-changes-surprises-interview|title=''Masked Singer'' Showrunner Promises Big Changes for Season 3, Says Cast is \"Unbelievably Interesting\"|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 31, 2020|access-date=April 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207084115/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8549443/masked-singer-showrunner-season-3-changes-surprises-interview|archive-date=February 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:CBS TelevisionCity02.jpg|thumb|left|alt=refer to caption|The series is filmed at [[Television City]] studios in Los Angeles.]]\nThe series is filmed at [[Television City]] in Los Angeles, California in a studio that seats 380 people.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Keegan|first=Kayla|title=Going to a ''Masked Singer'' Taping Is Like Visiting a Top-Secret CIA Compound|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|website=[[Good Housekeeping]]|access-date=April 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405081745/https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|archive-date=April 5, 2020|date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first season was filmed from June 4, 2018, to June 28, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|access-date=April 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526204614/http://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=May 26, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> the second from July 1, 2019, to August 19, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|access-date=April 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714070242/http://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=July 14, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the third from December 19, 2019, to February 28, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|access-date=April 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228120213/https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> Despite the show having a much shorter filming schedule than most television shows,<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\">{{cite web|last=VanDerWerff|first=Todd|title=''The Masked Singer'' is one of TV\u2019s oddest shows. Here\u2019s how it was made.|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/2/27/18241269/masked-singer-interview-finale-recap-preview|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=April 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402114050/https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/2/27/18241269/masked-singer-interview-finale-recap-preview|archive-date=April 2, 2019|date=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> filming dates were occasionally moved to accommodate celebrities' other activities.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\">{{cite web|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|title=''The Masked Singer'' Boss on Importance of Contestant Secrecy|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-contestant-secrecy-hippo-unmasked-1203089606/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=April 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706101843/https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-contestant-secrecy-hippo-unmasked-1203089606/|archive-date=July 6, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Plestis, the contestants sing live and their voices remain unedited in [[post-production]].<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Thicke noted that guessing is a challenge for the panelists due to sound issues in the studio often obscuring performers' voices and that it takes multiple performances for them to catch on to who the celebrity might be. Plestis said the panelists' guesses are heavily edited due to their extensiveness. They are forbidden from [[Google (verb)|googling]] possible answers to the clues presented to them between the filming of episodes.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/><ref name=\"ADW Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Jason|title=How The Masked Singer Became Broadcast\u2019s Biggest Midseason Hit|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/how-the-masked-singer-became-broadcasts-biggest-midseason-hit/|website=[[Adweek]]|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513171046/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/how-the-masked-singer-became-broadcasts-biggest-midseason-hit/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Before the participants taking off their masks, the producers film the entire studio audience acting out how they would react to the moment, with only a select twenty \"extremely well-vetted\" people remaining in the audience during the actual reveal.<ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/>\n\n===Security===\nBefore each of the competitors is unmasked, the show's staff undertakes significant security measures to prevent the participants' identities from leaking, many of which, according to Plestis, originate from his visits to the sets of the South Korean and Thai versions of the show.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> Everyone that is involved in the series signs [[Non-disclosure agreement|non-disclosure agreements]] (NDAs). After the celebrities have been confirmed to appear on the show, they are allowed to inform a few others who also sign NDAs.<ref name=\"VAR Dec 18\"/> They are not allowed to discuss their participation on the show until the day the episode of their reveal airs on television.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Before arriving on the show's set, the participants and their family, friends, and agents are disguised and driven from a neutral location.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> The manager of [[Joey Fatone]], the Rabbit in the first season, said he was picked up at a [[7-Eleven]] near Television City, given a disguise, and then driven inside the gate.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> Likewise, [[Adrienne Bailon]], the Flamingo in the second season, said she was taken to the set inside of an unmarked black car and only discussed her involvement on the show with producers in a \"secret warehouse.\"<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/>\n\nThe series' security team is almost as large as the production crew.<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\"/> While on set, each participant is disguised with a mask, visor, gloves, oversized sweatshirt, and pants to prevent their skin from showing<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> and are escorted by security guards.<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\"/> {{nobr|Twenty-five}} people knew the actual identities of the contestants in advance of the first season, though they never referred to them as such on set, in phone calls, or in emails regarding the show. Ibarra stated that the show's writers and director were uninformed of the participants' identities until they were unmasked. [[Margaret Cho]], the Poodle in the first season, said she never encountered another participant due to the performers' rehearsals occurring at varying times and locations.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/>\n\n===Costumes===\n[[File:Marina Toybina.png|thumb|upright=0.8|alt=refer to caption|The costumes for the series are designed by Marina Toybina.]]\nPlestis described the series' costumes as \"extremely critical\" to the show. With some costing thousands of dollars, he adds that \"so much money\" is invested in them.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\"/><ref name=\"LA Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Villareal|first=Yvonne|title=''The Masked Singer'' costume designer takes us inside TV\u2019s most colorful closet|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-masked-singer-fox-costumes-marina-toybina-20190206-story.html|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=September 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233157/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-masked-singer-fox-costumes-marina-toybina-20190206-story.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  They are designed by {{nobr|[[Emmy Award]]-winner}} Marina Toybina. The concepts for the costumes are her own and are inspired by a variety of sources. She begins by sketching each costume idea with a pencil and then gives the drawings to one of her friends who creates a digital version. After the costume concepts are shared with the show's producers and Fox executives who decide which designs will be featured during a season, Toybina buys all of the necessary fabrics herself and collaborates with a team of twenty to thirty people to custom-make them.<ref name=\"DH Costume\">{{cite web|last=Grobar|first=Matt|title=How \u2018The Masked Singer\u2019 Costume Designer Marina Toybina Crafted 12 Full-Body Art Pieces In Under Two Months|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina-emmys-fox-interview-1202660891/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|access-date=September 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913182757/https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina-emmys-fox-interview-1202660891/|archive-date=September 13, 2019|date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Each costume takes about two months to create in total; the masks are built in about one week and are designed to prevent echoes.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/><ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Beginning as a wire mesh; foam is gradually added around the mask, creating an {{nobr|easy-to-wear helmet}} shape for the performer.<ref name=\"TC Mar 1\">{{cite web|last=Spellings|first=Sarah|title=How Heavy Were Those ''The Masked Singer'' Masks, Anyway?|url=https://www.thecut.com/2019/03/interview-the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#The Cut|The Cut]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233201/https://www.thecut.com/2019/03/interview-the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|date=March 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"AVC\">{{cite web|title=How The Masked Singer's costume designer dreams up the show's insane outfits|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eShX30efZd8|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|date=August 29, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Toybina says she purposely uses foam for the costumes instead of wood or metal as their heavy weight would make the costumes difficult to move around in.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> As \"the draping and the handwork [for the costumes are] all done the old school way,\" she cites fashion designers such as [[Alexander McQueen]], [[Thierry Mugler]], and [[Hussein Chalayan]] as inspirations.<ref name=\"HP Costume\">{{cite web|last=Frank|first=Priscilla|title=The Maniacal Costume Designer Behind 'The Masked Singer' Speaks|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/costume-designer-masked-singer-marina-toybina_n_5c4f3992e4b0f43e41099257|url-status=live|website=[[HuffPost]]|publisher=[[Verizon Media]]|access-date=September 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915172544/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/costume-designer-masked-singer-marina-toybina_n_5c4f3992e4b0f43e41099257|archive-date=September 15, 2019|date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"VAR Jan 10\">{{cite web|last=Friedlander|first=Whitney|title=Meet the ''Masked Singer'' Costume Designer Behind Those Elaborate Looks|url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/masked-singer-costume-designer-1203103034/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222072254/https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/masked-singer-costume-designer-1203103034/|archive-date=December 22, 2019|date=January 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VF Costume\">{{cite magazine|last=Bradley|first=Laura|date=January 23, 2019|title=How The Masked Singer Dreamed Up Those Delightfully Delirious Costumes|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/the-masked-singer-costumes-designer-marina-toybina|url-status=live|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915040813/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/the-masked-singer-costumes-designer-marina-toybina|archive-date=September 15, 2019|access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> Toybina says the majority of costumes turn out identical to her sketches.<ref name=\"VF Costume\"/>\n\nToybina personally meets with each contestant to choose which costume they want to wear on the show.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/><ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Before being worn by a participant, the costumes ability to project the voice are tested with singers. <ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Due to time constraints, a maximum of two fittings are conducted with each celebrity at a \"very, very private {{nobr|hidden-away}}\" location<ref name=\"VAR Jan 10\"/> (either the costume shop or Toybina's own studio)<ref name=\"VF Costume\"/> in which the costumes are tested with a vocal coach to be sure the celebrities can sing and hear clearly.<ref name=\"TVI Sep 24\">{{cite web|last=Halterman|first=Jim|title=''The Masked Singer'' Season 2 Disguises by the Numbers|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/810949/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes-preview/|website=TV Insider|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928183052/https://www.tvinsider.com/810949/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes-preview/|archive-date=September 28, 2019|date=September 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VUL Sep 25\">{{cite web|last=McHenry|first=Jackson|title=''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Costume Designer Breaks Down All 16 Egg-cellent New Looks|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and destination sites|Vulture]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221030001/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The participants are assisted by a production crew that helps them take their costumes on and off during filming. Ibarra notes the difficulty contestants have in getting to the stage and seeing when on performing it.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> As there are no backup costumes, each is sanitized and repaired if needed between episodes.<ref name=\"HP Costume\"/><ref name=\"TVI Sep 24\"/>\n\nFor their work on the first season's finale, Toybina and costume supervisor Grainne O'Sullivan received a [[Creative Arts Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming|Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming]].<ref name=\"Emmy 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2019/outstanding-costumes-for-a-variety-program-or-a-special|title=Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming Nominees/Winners 2019|website=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205042123/https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2019/outstanding-costumes-for-a-variety-program-or-a-special|archive-date=December 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the second season, Toybina won a [[Costume Designers Guild#Costume Designers Guild Awards|Costume Designers Guild Award]] in the Excellence in Variety, Reality-Competition, Live Television category in recognition of her work on the final episode.<ref name=\"CAG 2020\">{{cite web|last=Tangcay|first=Jazz|title=''Hustlers'', ''Jojo Rabbit'' and ''Queen & Slim'' Receive Costume Design Nominations|url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/news/costume-designers-guild-awards-nominations-2020-1203430594/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|date=December 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205185900/https://variety.com/2019/artisans/news/costume-designers-guild-awards-nominations-2020-1203430594/|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Series overview==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! colspan=\"2\" | Number of\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Duration\n! colspan=\"3\" | Finalists\n|-\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | Celebrities\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | Weeks\n! background:gold;\" align=\"center\" | Winner\n! background:silver;\" align=\"center\"| Runner-up\n! background:tan;\" align=\"center\" | Third place\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|1]]\n| 