Mask is Lifted\")\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"Emmy 2019\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Critics' Choice Real TV Awards\n| [[1st Critics' Choice Real TV Awards|2019]]\n| Competition Series: Talent/Variety\n| ''The Masked Singer''\n| {{won}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|last1=Montgomery|first1=Daniel|title=Winners of the Inaugural Critics' Choice Real TV Awards|url=http://www.criticschoice.com/critics-choice-real-tv-awards/|publisher=[[Broadcast Film Critics Association]]|access-date=April 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918170057/http://www.criticschoice.com/critics-choice-real-tv-awards/|archive-date=September 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Gold Derby]] TV Awards\n| 2019\n| Competition Program\n| ''The Masked Singer''\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|last1=Montgomery|first1=Daniel|last2=Dixon|first2=Marcus James|last3=Beachum|first3=Chris|last4=Eng|first4=Joyce|last5=Sheehan|first5=Paul|last6=Wloszczyna|first6=Susan|title=Gold Derby TV Awards winners 2019: ''Game of Thrones'' and ''Fleabag'' rule, but voters spread the wealth|url=https://www.goldderby.com/article/2019/gold-derby-tv-awards-winners-2019-game-of-thrones-fleabag-news/|website=[[Gold Derby]]|access-date=April 5, 2020|date=September 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406001043/https://www.goldderby.com/article/2019/gold-derby-tv-awards-winners-2019-game-of-thrones-fleabag-news/|archive-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2020 Kids' Choice Awards|TBA]]\n| Favorite Reality Show\n| ''The Masked Singer''\n| {{pending}}\n| style=text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/avengers-end-game-leads-nickelodeons-kids-choice-awards-nominations-billie-eilish-taylor-swift-chance-the-rapper-full-list-1202859259/|title=''Avengers: Endgame'' Leads Nickelodeon\u2019s Kids\u2019 Choice Awards Nominations; Chance The Rapper Set As Host|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Denise Petski|date=February 13, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313113934/https://deadline.com/2020/02/avengers-end-game-leads-nickelodeons-kids-choice-awards-nominations-billie-eilish-taylor-swift-chance-the-rapper-full-list-1202859259/|archive-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| Favorite TV Host\n| [[Nick Cannon]]\n| {{pending}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[MTV Movie & TV Awards]]\n| [[2019 MTV Movie & TV Awards|2019]]\n| Best Host\n| Nick Cannon\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|last=Bell|first=Crystal|title=2019 MTV Movie & TV Awards Winners: See the Full List|url=https://www.mtv.ca/mtv-movie-and-tv-awards-winners/|website=[[MTV]]|access-date=June 20, 2019|date=June 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620221134/https://www.mtv.ca/mtv-movie-and-tv-awards-winners/|archive-date=June 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[People's Choice Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[45th People's Choice Awards|2019]]\n| The Competition Show of 2019\n| ''The Masked Singer''\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web|last=Evans|first=Greg|title=E! People\u2019s Choice Awards Finalists Announced; Voting Open Through Oct. 18 \u2013 Complete List|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/e-peoples-choice-awards-finalists-complete-list-1202710461|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|date=September 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914161428/https://deadline.com/2019/09/e-peoples-choice-awards-finalists-complete-list-1202710461/|archive-date=September 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| The Competition Contestant of 2019\n| [[T-Pain]]\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Producers Guild of America Award|Producers Guild of America Awards]]\n| [[31st Producers Guild of America Awards|2020]]\n| Outstanding Producer of Game & Competition Television \n| Craig Plestis, Izzie Pick Ibarra, Nikki Varhely-Gillingham, Rosie Seitchik, Stacey Thomas-Muir, Nick Cannon, Ashley Sylvester, Lindsay Tuggle, Pete Cooksley, Chelsea Candelaria, Anne Chanthavong, Zo\u00eb Ritchken, Deena Katz, Erin Brady, Jeff Kmiotek, Lexi Shoemaker\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|title=Nominations Announced in Motion Pictures and Television Programs Categories - 2020 Awards|url=https://www.producersguild.org/news/483748/|website=[[Producers Guild of America]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215044411/https://www.producersguild.org/news/483748/|archive-date=February 15, 2020|date=January 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Brunico Communications|Realscreen Awards]]\n| 2020\n| Talent & Studio-Based Competition\n| ''The Masked Singer''\n| {{won}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|title=2020 Winners & Nominees|url=https://awards.realscreen.com/Winners/Winner/2020|website=Realscreen|publisher=[[Brunico Communications]]|access-date=April 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405233615/https://awards.realscreen.com/Winners/Winner/2020|archive-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Shorty Awards]]\n| [[11th Shorty Awards|2019]]\n| Best in Entertainment Sites and Apps \n| ''The Masked Singer'' Social Hub\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|title=''The Masked Singer'' Social Hub |url=https://shortyawards.com/11th/the-masked-singer-social-hub|website=[[Shorty Awards]]|access-date=April 5, 2019|date=January 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405064238/https://shortyawards.com/11th/the-masked-singer-social-hub|archive-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| [[2019 Teen Choice Awards|2019]]\n| Choice Reality TV Show\n| ''The Masked Singer''\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|last=Kaufran|first=Gil|title=Lil Nas X & Post Malone Lead 2019 Teen Choice Awards Nominations: See the List|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8516707/2019-teen-choice-awards-nominations|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|date=June 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326005330/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8516707/2019-teen-choice-awards-nominations|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Critical response===\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Kristen Baldwin felt the show was captivating but said the judges were unfit to be critiquing singers and criticized them for not paying attention to the clues or performances.<ref>{{cite web|last=Baldwin|first=Kristen|title=Fox's ''The Masked Singer'': What the holy hell is this?|url=https://ew.com/tv-reviews/2019/01/02/the-masked-singer-fox-recap/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920204236/https://ew.com/tv-reviews/2019/01/02/the-masked-singer-fox-recap/|archive-date=April 20, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Likewise, Kelly Lawler of ''[[USA Today]]'' attributed the series' success to its brilliant concept only and named the judging panel the worst in reality television history. She described Jeong as {{nobr|over-the-top}}, Scherzinger as boring, Thicke as too serious, and McCarthy as inexperienced<ref>{{cite web|last=Lawler|first=Kelly|title=The 5 best (and 5 worst) reality-TV show judging panels of all time|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/02/25/reality-tv-judges-5-best-and-5-worst-panels-all-time-the-voice-american-idol-simon-cowell-rupaul/2937947002/|website=[[USA Today]]|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401114701/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/02/25/reality-tv-judges-5-best-and-5-worst-panels-all-time-the-voice-american-idol-simon-cowell-rupaul/2937947002/|archive-date=April 1, 2020|date=February 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Similarly, [[Matt Zoller Seitz]] of ''Vulture'' lambasted the presence of McCarthy as a judge (referring to her {{nobr|[[Jenny McCarthy#Autism activism and views on vaccines|prominent]] [[vaccine hesitancy|anti-vaccine]]}} views) but praised the chemistry between her and the other judges. He criticized the way the show's producers edit their guesses, stating they should cut out repetitive comments more often.<ref>{{cite web|last=Seitz|first=Matt Zoller|author-link=Matt Zoller Seitz|title=How Is The Masked Singer Real?|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-review.html|website=Vulture|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218162823/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-review.html|archive-date=December 18, 2019|date=September 26, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Others from ''Vulture'' also derided the editing as awkward but praised the costumes as fantastic and noted that they came to life on stage, describing the timelessness of the Egg, gorgeousness of the Butterfly, and badass attitude of the Rottweiler. However, they felt the judges were mindless and unfunny, condemning them for spoiling the show's innovative concept with distracting statements.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wright|first=Megh|title=Egg Was Too Pure for This Terrible World|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/goodbye-egg.html|website=Vulture|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926201418/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/goodbye-egg.html|archive-date=September 26, 2019|date=September 26, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=VanArendonk|first=Kathryn|title=''The Masked Singer'' Is a Reality-TV Fever Dream|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|website=Vulture|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225230817/https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|archive-date=December 25, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAfter attended a taping of the show, Kayla Keegan of ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'' said she appreciated the detailing of the costumes, praising Toybina's skill in designing them.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/>  Writing for ''[[The Atlantic]]'', Megan Garber compared the series' format to that of [[Police procedural|crime procedural]] ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]'' due to its mystery elements.<ref name=\"ATL Feb 28\">{{cite news|last=Garber|first=Megan|title=''The Masked Singer'' Lets You In on the Scam|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/02/masked-singer-finale-what-show-really-reveals/583882/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=April 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308121421/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/02/masked-singer-finale-what-show-really-reveals/583882/|archive-date=March 8, 2020|date=February 28, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=limited}}</ref> Emily Yahr of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' described the show as crazy but said Cannon was perfect as host, noting his years of experience in the same role on ''[[America's Got Talent]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Yahr|first=Emily|title=Yes, that was real life: ''The Masked Singer'' premiered and was even weirder than you imagined|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|website=Vulture|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225230817/https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|archive-date=December 25, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[John Doyle (critic)|John Doyle]] called Cannon inarticulate and described the judges as [[Camp (style)|cheesy]] and irrelevant. He characterized the show as a wacky and dumb version of [[Charades]] but acknowledged that it is popular because of its simplicity. Doyle cited the series as an example of a cultural shift in the United States away from the competitive and often exploitative nature of shows such as ''[[American Idol]]'' towards a higher level of positivity among reality television series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Doyle|first=John|author-link=John Doyle (critic)|title=Dumb simplicity: Why The Masked Singer is a massive TV hit|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/article-dumb-simplicity-why-the-masked-singer-is-a-massive-tv-hit/|website=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218163655/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/article-dumb-simplicity-why-the-masked-singer-is-a-massive-tv-hit/|archive-date=December 18, 2019|date=November 4, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Likewise, Daniel D'Addario of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described the show as relaxing and refreshing, calling it a return to form for television as the series possesses the now-rare ability to uplift and unite people. He commended the show's judges, comparing them to the original ''American Idol'' judges as non-experts in their fields, noting their common, implausible [[A-list]] celebrity guesses. He also praised the show's positive platform for allowing celebrities to express themselves freely even if they are not professional singers.<ref>{{cite web|last=D'Addario|first=Daniel|title=In Praise of ''The Masked Singer'', TV's Last Uniter (Column)|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/columns/masked-singer-super-bowl-1203485315/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210183913/https://variety.com/2020/tv/columns/masked-singer-super-bowl-1203485315/|archive-date=February 10, 2020|date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Cultural impact===\nFans of the show take part in guessing on [[Twitter]] each time an episode airs.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> The series is discussed on numerous [[podcast|podcasts]] and has generated its own [[Reddit#Subreddit|thread]] on [[Reddit]].<ref name=\"ATL Feb 28\"/> \n\nMichael Schneider of ''Variety'' said the series' success has sparked a revitalization of reality television in the United States, comparing it to [[Fox Broadcasting Company#2000s: Rise to ratings leadership, the American Idol effect, and fierce rivalry with CBS|the early 2000s]] when Fox's many reality series received high ratings. The revivals of ''[[Paradise Hotel]]'' and ''[[Temptation Island]]'' by Fox and [[USA Network]], respectively, have been credited to the show's success, as have the American versions of ''[[Love Island (American TV series)|Love Island]]'' and ''[[I Can See Your Voice (American game show)|I Can See Your Voice]]''. Rob Wade, the President of Fox Alternative Entertainment, has described a shift in the way new shows are [[sales presentation|pitched]] since the series premiered, noting there is an increased openness to new ideas. Wade also said the heads of almost all television networks thanked him for the series giving them a \"[[blank cheque|carte blanche]]\" to take new programming risks.<ref name=\"VAR Feb 19\">{{cite news|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=Who Is That Masked B-Lister?|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48002572/the-gazette/|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]|agency=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404200853/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48002572/the-gazette/|archive-date=April 4, 2020|date=February 19, 2019|url-status=live|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nThe show was the first in the [[Masked Singer|''Masked Singer'' franchise]] to air outside of Asia and its success has been attributed to at least ten local adaptations of the series, including versions in [[The Masked Singer Austria|Austria]], Peru, and the [[The Masked Singer (British TV series)|United Kingdom]]. The producers of the British series said they were inspired to adapt the format after watching an episode of the American version.<ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> The series has also been credited with reinvigorating the costume genre of television. Interest in adapting other costume-centered franchises such as ''[[Wild Things (game show)|Wild Things]]'' and ''[[Sexy Beasts]]'' has increased around the world since the show premiered.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\"/>\n\n===Television ratings===\n''The Masked Singer'' premiered in {{nobr|January 2019}} as the highest rated [[reality television|unscripted]] television series debut since ''[[The X Factor (American TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in 2011. Following three days of DVR viewing, the first episode's {{nobr|18\u201349 rating}} grew by {{nobr|30 percent\u2014the}} highest increase ever for a premiere in the show's genre.<ref>{{cite web|last=Holloway|first=Daniel|title=''The Masked Singer'' Scores Biggest Live+3 Lift Ever for Unscripted Series|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/masked-singer-ratings-1203101918/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125164644/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/masked-singer-ratings-1203101918/|archive-date=December 22, 2019|date=January 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Although initially dropping, ratings grew towards the end of the season, and the finale became the most watched episode.<ref name=\"ADW Sep 25\">{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Jason|title=How Freshman Hit ''The Masked Singer'' Will Try to Avoid a Sophomore Slump|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/masked-singer-season-2-what-to-expect/|website=[[Adweek]]|access-date=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926021058/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/masked-singer-season-2-what-to-expect/|archive-date=September 26, 2019|date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The show concluded the [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319 television season]] as the highest rated new series among adults {{nobr|18\u201349}}, averaging a {{nobr|2.6 rating}} throughout all ten episodes,<ref name=\"THR May 23\"/> and as the highest rated entertainment series among teens, {{nobr|men 18\u201334,}} {{nobr|adults 18\u201334,}} and {{nobr|adults 18\u201349.}}<ref name=\"ADW Oct 20\">{{cite web|title=The 2019 TV Hot List: The Year\u2019s Biggest and Buzziest Shows, Networks and People|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/the-2019-tv-hot-list-the-years-biggest-and-buzziest-shows-networks-and-people/4/|website=[[Adweek]]|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230042701/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/the-2019-tv-hot-list-the-years-biggest-and-buzziest-shows-networks-and-people/4/|archive-date=December 30, 2019|date=October 20, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Among unscripted series, it was the first to rank {{nobr|number-one}} in the genre in its first season since ''[[Joe Millionaire]]'' in 2003.<ref name=\"VAR Feb 19\"/> \n\nThe second season premiered {{nobr|17 percent}} lower than the previous, though it was mostly in line with the first season's average.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thorne|first=Will|title=TV Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' Easily Wins Wednesday|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/tv-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-2-premiere-1203350350/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927145835/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/tv-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-2-premiere-1203350350/|archive-date=September 27, 2019|date=September 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The finale's ratings also dropped compared to the first season, although the broadcast was up {{nobr|20 percent}} in viewers from the previous week.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|title=''The Masked Singer'' & ''Survivor'' Finales, ''Live In Front Of A Studio Audience'' Ratings Dip Amid Primetime Impeachment Vote|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/the-masked-singer-finale-ratings-survivor-winner-live-in-front-of-a-studio-audience-1202813754/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304071423/https://deadline.com/2019/12/the-masked-singer-finale-ratings-survivor-winner-live-in-front-of-a-studio-audience-1202813754/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Deadline Hollywood]] cited the second season as a major reason why {{nobr|Fox\u2014for}} the first time in the network's {{nobr|history\u2014ranked}} number-one in fall entertainment programming,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie||last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|title=Fox Tops Fall Demo Ratings For First Time In Decade; NBC Snaps CBS\u2019 Total Viewers Streak|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/tv-ratings-fall-2019-fox-wins-nbc-the-masked-singer-sunday-night-football-1202817673/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104191044/https://deadline.com/2019/12/tv-ratings-fall-2019-fox-wins-nbc-the-masked-singer-sunday-night-football-1202817673/|archive-date=January 4, 2020|date=December 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and ''[[Adweek]]'' named the show the \"Hottest {{nobr|Reality/Competition}} Series\" of 2019.<ref name=\"ADW Oct 20\"/> The third season, which premiered as the [[Super Bowl LIV]] [[list of Super Bowl lead-out programs|lead-out program]], was viewed by over {{nobr|23.7 million}} people and received an {{nobr|8.1 18\u201349 rating}}. While the episode was watched by more than the previous lead-out, ''[[The World's Best]]'' {{nobr|(22.2 million),}} and Fox's most-recent lead-out, 2017's ''[[24: Legacy]]'' {{nobr|(17.6 million),}} it was lower than the viewership of ''[[This Is Us]]'' {{nobr|(27 million)}} in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last=Adalian|first=Joseph|title=23 Million People Watched a Celebrity Pretend to Be a Robot on ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/the-masked-singer-super-bowl-ratings.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and destination sites|Vulture]]|access-date=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311162320/https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/the-masked-singer-super-bowl-ratings.html|archive-date=March 11, 2020|date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> According to ''[[Ad Age]]'', the series was one of two non-NFL programs to cost at least $200,000 per thirty seconds of advertising during the [[2019\u201320 United States network television schedule|2019\u201320 television season]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Adgate|first=Brad|title=TV Ad Rates (But Not Ad Revenue) Are Dropping|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bradadgate/2019/10/15/tv-ad-rates-but-not-ad-revenue-are-dropping/|website=[[Forbes]]|access-date=April 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408171217/https://www.forbes.com/sites/bradadgate/2019/10/15/tv-ad-rates-but-not-ad-revenue-are-dropping/|archive-date=April 8, 2020|date=October 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"width:14%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | Timeslot\n([[Eastern Time Zone (North America)|ET]], [[UTC\u20135]])\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | Episodes\n! colspan=\"2\" | First aired\n! colspan=\"2\" | Last aired\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | TV season\n! style=\"width:28%;\" colspan=\"4\" | Averages\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%;\" | Date\n! style=\"width:8%;\" | Viewers<br>(millions)\n! style=\"width:10%;\" | Date\n! style=\"width:8%;\" | Viewers<br>(millions)\n! style=\"width:7%; | Viewership<br>ranking\n! style=\"width:7%; | Viewers<br>(millions)\n! style=\"width:7%; | 18\u201349<br>ranking\n! style=\"width:7%; | 18\u201349<br>rating\n|-\n| [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|1]]\n| Wednesday 9:00&nbsp;p.m.\n| 10\n| January 2, 2019\n| 9.37<ref>{{cite web|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-on-fox-scores-tvs-highest-rated-unscripted-series-launch-in-seven-years/|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' on Fox Scores TV\u2019s Highest-Rated Unscripted Series Launch in Seven Years|work=Programming Insider|date=January 4, 2019|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323022456/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-on-fox-scores-tvs-highest-rated-unscripted-series-launch-in-seven-years/|archive-date=March 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| February 27, 2019\n| 11.48<ref>{{cite web|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155952/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-michael-cohen-hearing-draws-significant-audience-figures-in-daytime-across-various-networks/|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: Michael Cohen Hearing Draws Significant Audience Figures in Daytime Across Various Networks|work=Programming Insider|date=February 28, 2019|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155952/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-michael-cohen-hearing-draws-significant-audience-figures-in-daytime-across-various-networks/|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319]]\n| 16\n| 8.17<ref name=\"THR May 23\">{{cite web|last=Porter|first=Rick|title=2018-19 TV Season Ratings: 90 Percent of Veteran Broadcast Shows Fall|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ratings-broadcast-network-series-2018-19-1213344|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|date=May 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617113702/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ratings-broadcast-network-series-2018-19-1213344|archive-date=June 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| 5\n| 2.6<ref name=\"THR May 23\"/>\n|-\n| [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|2]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Wednesday 8:00&nbsp;p.m.\n| 13\n| September 25, 2019\n| 8.03<ref>{{cite web|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' Season Premiere Helps Fox to Dominate Prime Time as it Doubled the Runner-Up Network in Adults 18-49|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-premiere-helps-fox-to-dominate-prime-time-as-it-doubled-the-runner-up-network-in-adults-18-49/|website=Programming Insider|access-date=March 27, 2020|date=September 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005182232/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-premiere-helps-fox-to-dominate-prime-time-as-it-doubled-the-runner-up-network-in-adults-18-49/|archive-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| December 18, 2019\n| 8.37<ref name=\"2.12/13\">{{cite web|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: Over 12 Million Watch Impeachment Vote Coverage Across Various Cable News Stations|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-over-12-million-watch-impeachment-vote-coverage-across-various-cable-news-stations/|website=Programming Insider|access-date=March 27, 2020|date=December 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328034025/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-over-12-million-watch-impeachment-vote-coverage-across-various-cable-news-stations/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2019\u201320 United States network television schedule|2019\u201320]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBA}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBA}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBA}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBA}}\n|-\n| [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|3]]\n| {{n/a|TBA}}\n| February 2, 2020\n| 23.78<ref>{{cite web|url=https://programminginsider.com/sunday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-third-season-premiere-on-fox-generates-second-largest-total-audience-and-adults-18-49-delivery-for-a-super-bowl-lead-out-in-five-years/|title=Sunday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' Third Season Premiere on Fox Generates Second-Largest Total Audience and Adults 18-49 Delivery for a Super Bowl Lead-Out in Five Years|work=Programming Insider|author=Douglas Pucci|date=February 11, 2020|access-date=February 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211224755/https://programminginsider.com/sunday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-third-season-premiere-on-fox-generates-second-largest-total-audience-and-adults-18-49-delivery-for-a-super-bowl-lead-out-in-five-years/|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| May 27, 2020<ref name=\"TFC Listings\"/>\n| {{n/a|TBA}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Spin-offs==\n===''The Masked Singer: After the Mask''===\n\nOn April 8, 2020, Fox announced that Nick Cannon will host an [[aftershow]] of the series titled ''The Masked Singer: After the Mask'' on Wednesdays at 9:00 p.m. for four weeks starting on April 22. He will host the show from his house and discuss the outcome of the preceding episode. The show will also feature remote appearances of celebrity guests as well as games and musical performances.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=''The Masked Singer'' After-Show, Hosted by Nick Cannon, to Launch on Fox|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/the-masked-singer-after-the-mask-nick-cannon-fox-1234574761/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 8, 2020|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Roots|first=Kimberly|title=''The Masked Singer'' to Get Aftershow|url=https://tvline.com/2020/04/08/the-masked-singer-aftershow-nick-cannon-season-3-fox/|website=[[TVLine]]|date=April 8, 2020|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''The Masked Dancer''===\nOn {{nobr|January 7, 2020,}} at the winter [[Television Critics Association]] press tour, Fox Alternative Entertainment and [[Warner Bros. Television]] announced that they had ordered a spin-off series, ''The Masked Dancer'', with [[Ellen DeGeneres]] as executive producer. DeGeneres had previously conducted ''The Masked Dancer'' as a recurring segment of her syndicated [[talk show]] ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', as a {{nobr|self-admitted}} parody of ''The Masked Singer''. DeGeneres stated that the show was \"gonna be just as fun and suspenseful\", but \"with a lot more [[krumping]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/the-masked-dancer-fox-partners-with-ellen-degeneres-on-the-masked-singer-spin-off-1202823169/|title=\u2018The Masked Dancer\u2019: Fox Partners With Ellen DeGeneres On \u2018The Masked Singer\u2019 Spinoff \u2013 TCA|last=White|first=Peter|last2=White|first2=Peter|date=January 7, 2020|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/pug-almost-passes-out-playing-ellen-degeneres-latest-masked-singer-ripoff-video/|title=A Pug Almost Passes Out Playing Ellen DeGeneres' Latest 'Masked Dancer'|date=February 18, 2019|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===National Tour===\nOn {{nobr|February 12, 2020,}} it was announced that the show would be getting a live national tour with shows in over forty-five cities. Beginning at the [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]] on {{nobr|May 28, 2020}}, the tour will feature two celebrity hosts as well as a local mystery celebrity who is unmasked at the end of each show.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20200212005953/en/MASKED-SINGER-Unveils-45-City-U.S.-National|title=THE MASKED SINGER Unveils 45+ City U.S. National Tour|via=[[Business Wire]]|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018The Masked Singer\u2019 Announces Nationwide Concert Tour This Summer|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/masked-singer-concert-tour-summer-1203502739/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Michael Schneider|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasts==\nThe series is broadcast by Fox in the United States and is [[simulcast]] by [[CTV Television Network|CTV]] in Canada since the second season. The show is available for streaming in the United States on Fox's website and [[Hulu]], and in Canada on CTV's website.<ref>{{cite press release|title= CTV Unveils 2019/20 Primetime Schedule, Featuring Dynamic Dramas with Big Stars and Big Stories|url=https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|publisher=[[Bell Media]]|access-date=April 5, 2020|date=June 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607044629/https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|archive-date=June 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Watch The Masked Singer|url=https://www.hulu.com/series/the-masked-singer-15209f88-6004-4d73-b993-3ff1a244f494|publisher=[[Hulu]]|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{sequence\n|prev=''[[The World's Best ]]''<br />[[Super Bowl LIII|2019]]\n|list=[[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|Super Bowl lead-out program]]<br />''The Masked Singer''<br />[[Super Bowl LIV|2020]]\n|next=TBA\n}}\n\n{{The Masked Singer (American TV series)}}\n{{Masked Singer series}}\n{{FOXNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masked Singer, The}}\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Fox Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:2010s American music television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2020s American music television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American game shows]]\n[[Category:American television series based on South Korean television series]]\n[[Category:Music competitions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl lead-out programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by Endemol]]\n[[Category:Television series by Fox Entertainment]]\n", "name_user": "Heartfox", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePanelists and host", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Masked_Singer_(American_TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "1931", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Year dab|1931}}\n{{Events by month|1931}}\n{{Year nav|1931}}\n{{C20 year in topic}}\n{{Year article header|1931}}\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==Events==\n\n===January===\n{{Main|January 1931}}\n* [[January]] \u2013 The [[National Committee for Modification of the Volstead Act]] is formed, to work for the [[repeal of Prohibition in the United States]].\n* [[January 2]] \u2013 [[South Dakota]] native [[Ernest Lawrence]] invents the [[cyclotron]], used to accelerate particles to study [[nuclear physics]].\n* [[January 3]] \u2013 [[Albert Einstein]] begins doing research at the [[California Institute of Technology]], along with astronomer [[Edwin Hubble]].\n* [[January 4]] \u2013 German pilot [[Elly Beinhorn]] begins her flight to Africa.\n* [[January 6]] \n** [[Thomas Edison]] submits his last [[patent]] application.\n**  In Chicago, [[CBMC]] hosts first meeting to address a greater purpose for business during [[The Great Depression]], packing over 800 seats in Chicago's Garrick Theatre.<ref>{{cite web |title=CBMC History |url=https://stlouis.cbmc.com/CBMC-History |accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[January 22]] \u2013 Sir [[Isaac Isaacs]] is sworn in as the first Australian-born [[Governor-General of Australia]].\n* [[January 25]] \u2013 [[Mohandas Gandhi]] is again released from imprisonment in India.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FauJL7LKXmkC&pg=PA127&dq=gandhi+prison&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiR3d7U5rrbAhXn7oMKHVKmDPEQ6AEISDAG#v=onepage&q=gandhi%20prison1931&f=false|title=Gandhi: The Man, His People, and the Empire|last=Gandhi|first=Rajmohan|date=2008|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520255708|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[January 27]] \u2013 [[Pierre Laval]] forms a government in France.\n* [[January 30]] \u2013 The movie ''[[City Lights]]'', starring [[Charlie Chaplin]], is released.\n\n===February===\n{{Main|February 1931}}\n* [[February 3]] \u2013 [[1931 Hawke's Bay earthquake|Hawke's Bay earthquake]]: Much of the New Zealand cities of Napier and Hastings are destroyed in an earthquake measuring 7.9 on the [[Richter magnitude scale|Richter scale]], killing 256 people.\n* [[February 4]] \u2013 Soviet leader [[Joseph Stalin]] gives a speech calling for rapid industrialization, arguing that only strong industrialized countries will win wars, while \"weak\" nations are \"beaten\". Stalin states: \"We are fifty or a hundred years behind the advanced countries. We must make good this distance in ten years. Either we do it, or they will crush us.\" The [[first five-year plan]] in the Soviet Union is intensified, for the industrialization and collectivization of agriculture.\n* [[February 10]] \u2013 Official inauguration ceremonies for New Delhi as the capital of India begin.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Delhi: The Inaugural Ceremony|newspaper=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=1931-02-11|issue=45744|page=12}}</ref>\n* [[February 11]] \u2013 [[Nazi Party|National Socialist]] (NSDAP) and [[German National People's Party]] (DNVP) members walk out of the German [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]], in protest against changes in the parliament's protocol, intended to limit heckling.  \n* [[February 12]] \u2013 ''[[Vatican Radio]]'' first broadcasts.\n* [[February 14]] \u2013 The original film version of ''[[Dracula (1931 English-language film)|Dracula]]'', with [[Bela Lugosi]], is released in the United States.\n* [[February 16]] \u2013 [[Pehr Evind Svinhufvud]] is elected president of Finland.\n* [[February 20]] \u2013 [[California]] gets the go-ahead by the [[United States Congress]], to build the [[San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge]].\n* [[February 21]] \u2013 [[Peru]]vian revolutionaries hijack a [[Ford Trimotor]] aeroplane, and demand that the pilot drop [[propaganda]] [[Flyer (pamphlet)|leaflet]]s over [[Lima]].\n\n[[File:Delhi India Government.jpg|thumb|230px|right|[[February 10]]: New Delhi becomes India's capital]]\n[[File:Ford Trimotor.jpg|thumb|200x200px|[[February 21]]: [[Ford Trimotor]] hijacked]]\n\n===March===\n{{Main|March 1931}}\n* [[March 1]] \n** The [[USS Arizona (BB-39)|USS ''Arizona'']] is placed back in full commission, after a refit.\n** Sir [[Oswald Mosley]] founds the [[New Party (UK)|New Party]] as a breakaway from the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in the United Kingdom. \n* [[March 3]] \u2013 ''[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]'' is adopted as the United States' [[National anthem]].\n* [[March 5]] \u2013 The British [[viceroy]] of India and [[Mohandas Gandhi]] sign the [[Gandhi\u2013Irwin Pact]].\n* [[March 7]] \u2013 The Finnish [[Parliament House, Helsinki|Parliament House]] opens in [[Helsinki]], Finland.\n* [[March 11]] \u2013 The ''[[Ready for Labour and Defence of the USSR]]'' programme, abbreviated as GTO, is introduced in the [[Soviet Union]].\n* [[March 17]] \u2013 [[Nevada]] legalizes [[gambling]].\n* [[March 19]] \u2013 The [[1931 Westminster St George's by-election|Westminster St George's by-election]] in the U.K. results in the victory of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate [[Duff Cooper]]. The by-election has been treated virtually as a referendum on the leadership of the Conservative leader [[Stanley Baldwin]], and Duff Cooper's victory ends the campaign by the press barons [[Lord Beaverbrook]] and [[Harold Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Rothermere|Viscount Rothermere]] to oust Baldwin. \n* [[March 23]] \u2013 Indian revolutionary leaders [[Bhagat Singh]], [[Shivaram Rajguru]] and [[Sukhdev Thapar]] are hanged for conspiracy to murder in the [[British Raj]].\n* [[March 25]] \u2013 The [[Scottsboro Boys]] are arrested in [[Alabama]], and charged with rape.\n* [[March 31]] \u2013 An [[1931 Nicaragua earthquake|earthquake]] destroys [[Managua]], [[Nicaragua]], killing 2,000 people.\n\n===April===\n{{Main|April 1931}}\n* [[April 1]] \u2013 The [[Second Encirclement Campaign against Jiangxi Soviet]] in China is launched by the [[Kuomintang]] government, to destroy the Communist forces in [[Jiangxi]] Province. \n* [[April 6]] \u2013 The Portuguese government declares martial law in [[Madeira]] and in the [[Azores]], because of the [[Madeira uprising]] in [[Funchal]].\n* [[April 12]] \u2013 Municipal elections in Spain, which are treated as a virtual referendum on the monarchy, result in the triumph for the republican parties. \n* [[April 14]] \u2013 The [[Second Spanish Republic]] is proclaimed in [[Madrid]]. Meanwhile, as a result of the victory of the [[Republican Left of Catalonia]], [[Francesc Maci\u00e0]] proclaims in [[Barcelona]] the [[Catalan Republic (1931)|Catalan Republic]], as a state of the Iberian Federation.\n* [[April 15]] \u2013 The [[Castellammarese War]] ends with the murder of [[Joe Masseria|Joe \"The Boss\" Masseria]], briefly leaving [[Salvatore Maranzano]] as [[capo dei capi]] (\"boss of all bosses\") of the [[American Mafia]]. Maranzano is himself murdered less than 6 months later, leading to the creation of the [[The Commission (mafia)|Commission]].\n* [[April 17]] \u2013 After the negotiations between the republican ministers of Spain and Catalonia, the Catalan Republic becomes the [[Generalitat of Catalonia]], a Catalan autonomous government inside the Spanish Republic.\n* [[April 22]] \u2013 [[Austria]], the [[United Kingdom|UK]], [[Denmark]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]], [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]], [[Sweden]] and the [[United States]] recognize the [[Second Spanish Republic|Spanish Republic]].\n* [[April 25]] \u2013 The automobile manufacturer [[Porsche]] is founded by [[Ferdinand Porsche]] in [[Stuttgart]].\n\n===May===\n{{Main|May 1931}}\n[[File:Manhattan at Dusk by slonecker.jpg|thumb|188x188px| [[May 1]]: [[Empire State Building]] is completed.]]\n* [[May 1]] \u2013 Construction of the [[Empire State Building]] is completed in New York City.\n* [[May 4]] \u2013 [[Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]] is re-elected president of [[Turkey]].\n* [[May 5]] \u2013 [[\u0130smet \u0130n\u00f6n\u00fc]] forms a new government in Turkey (7th government).\n* [[May 11]] \u2013 The ''[[Creditanstalt]]'', Austria's largest bank, goes bankrupt, beginning the banking collapse in Central Europe that causes a worldwide financial meltdown.\n* [[May 13]] \u2013 [[Paul Doumer]] is elected president of France.\n* [[May 14]] \u2013 [[\u00c5dalen shootings]]: Five people are killed in [[\u00c5dalen]], Sweden, when soldiers open fire on an unarmed trade union demonstration.\n* [[May 15]]\n** The Chinese Communists inflict a sharp defeat on the Kuomintang forces.\n** [[Pope Pius XI]] issues the [[encyclical]] ''[[Quadragesimo anno]]'', on the \"reconstruction of the social order\".\n* [[May 31]] \u2013 The Second Encirclement Campaign against Jiangxi Soviet ends in the defeat of the Kuomintang.\n\n===June===\n{{Main|June 1931}}\n* [[June 3]] \u2013 [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]'s ''[[The Persistence of Memory]]'' is put on display for the first time in Paris at the Galerie Pierre Colle.\n* [[June 5]] \u2013 German Chancellor Dr. [[Heinrich Br\u00fcning]] visits London, where he warns the British Prime Minister [[Ramsay MacDonald]] that the collapse of the Austrian banking system, caused by the bankruptcy of the ''Creditanstalt'', has left the entire German banking system on the verge of collapse.\n* [[June 12]] \u2013 English cricketer [[Charlie Parker (cricketer)|Charlie Parker]] equals [[J. T. Hearne]]'s record for the earliest date to reach 100 wickets.\n* [[June 14]] \u2013 [[Saint-Philibert disaster]]: The overloaded pleasure craft ''Saint-Philibert'', carrying trippers home to Nantes from the \u00cele de Noirmoutier, sinks at the mouth of the River [[Loire]] in France; over 450 drown.\n* [[June 19]]\n** In an attempt to stop the banking crisis in Central Europe from causing a worldwide financial meltdown, U.S. President [[Herbert Hoover]] issues the [[Hoover Moratorium]].\n** The [[Geneva Convention (1929)]] relative to the treatment of [[prisoners of war]] enters into force.\n* [[June 23]]\u2013[[July 1]] \u2013 [[Wiley Post]] and [[Harold Gatty]] accomplish the first round-the-world flight in a single-engine plane, flying eastabout from [[Roosevelt Field (airport)|Roosevelt Field]], New York, in 8 days, 15 hours, 51 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centennialofflight.gov/essay/Explorers_Record_Setters_and_Daredevils/Wiley_Post/EX27.htm|publisher=centennialofflight.gov|title=Wiley Post|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008043851/http://www.centennialofflight.gov/essay/Explorers_Record_Setters_and_Daredevils/Wiley_Post/EX27.htm |archivedate=October 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n{{Main|July 1931}}\n* [[July]] \u2013 [[John Haven Emerson]] of [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] perfects his [[negative pressure ventilator]] (\"iron lung\"), just in time for the growing [[polio]] epidemic.\n* [[July 1]] \u2013 The rebuilt [[Milano Centrale railway station]] officially opens in Italy.\n* [[July 9]] \u2013 Irish racing driver [[Kaye Don]] breaks the world [[water speed record]] at Lake Garda, Italy.<ref>''BBC History'', July 2011, p12.</ref>\n* [[July 10]] \u2013 Norway issues a royal proclamation claiming the uninhabited part of eastern [[Greenland]] as [[Erik the Red's Land]].\n* [[July 13]] \u2013 Royal soldiers shoot and kill 22 people demonstrating against the [[Maharaja]] [[Hari Singh]], of the Indian princely state of [[Kashmir and Jammu (princely state)|Kashmir and Jammu]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/jammu-and-kashmir/jandk-observes-martyrs-day-cm-omar-pays-tributes_719325.html|title=J&K observes Martyrs` day: CM Omar pays tributes|date=2011-07-13|work=Zee News|accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>\n* [[July 16]] \u2013 Emperor [[Haile Selassie]] signs the first [[1931 Constitution of Ethiopia|Constitution of Ethiopia]].\n* [[July 26]] \u2013 The millennialist [[Bible Student movement]] adopts the name [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], at a meeting in [[Columbus, Ohio]].\n* [[July 31]] \u2013 The [[May Report]] in the United Kingdom recommends extensive cuts to government expenditure. This produces a political crisis, as many members of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (at this time in government) object to the proposals.\n\n===August===\n{{Main|August 1931}}\n* The [[1931 China floods]] reach their peak, in possibly the deadliest natural disaster yet recorded.\n* [[Warner Brothers]] releases the first [[Merrie Melodies]] cartoon, ''[[Lady, Play Your Mandolin!|Lady, Play Your Mandolin]]''.\n* [[August 2]] \u2013 [[Murder of Paul Anlauf and Franz Lenck]]: Two [[Berlin]] police officers are killed by Communists.\n* [[August 9]] \u2013 A referendum in [[Free State of Prussia|Prussia]] for dissolving the ''Landtag'' ends with the \"yes\" side winning 37% of the vote, which is insufficient for calling the early elections. The elections are intended to remove the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democratic Party]] (SPD) government of [[Otto Braun]], which is one of the strongest forces for democracy in Germany. Supporting the \"yes\" side were the [[NSDAP]], the [[DNVP]] and the [[Communist Party of Germany|Communist Party]] (KPD), while supporting the \"no\" side were the SPD and ''[[Zentrumspartei|Zentrum]]''. \n* [[August 11]] \u2013 A run on the British pound leads to a political and economic crisis in Britain. (See [[European banking crisis of 1931]])\n* [[August 24]] \u2013 The [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Government of [[Ramsay MacDonald]] resigns in Britain, replaced by a [[National Government (United Kingdom)|National Government]] of people drawn from all parties, also under MacDonald.\n\n===September===\n{{Main|September 1931}}\n[[File:J\u012duy\u012bb\u0101 L\u00ecsh\u012d B\u00f3w\u00f9gu\u0103n\u4e5d\u30fb\u4e00\u516b\u6b74\u53f2\u535a\u7269\u9928106997.JPG|thumb|[[September 18]]: The [[Mukden Incident]]: Incident Museum in [[Shenyang]]|230x230px]]\n* [[September 5]] \u2013 [[John Thomson (footballer, born 1909)|John Thomson]], Scottish [[association football|football]] player, dies as the result of an accident, during a [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\u2013[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] match.\n* [[September 7]] \u2013 The [[Round Table Conferences (India)#Second Round Table Conference (September \u2013 December 1931)|Second Round Table Conference]] on the constitutional future of India opens in London; [[Mahatma Gandhi]] represents the [[Indian National Congress]].\n* [[September 10]] \u2013 The worst [[1931 Belize hurricane|hurricane]] in [[Belize|British Honduras]] history kills an estimated 1,500.\n* [[September 15]] \u2013 [[Invergordon Mutiny]]: [[Strike action|Strikes]] are called in the British [[Royal Navy]], due to decreased pay.\n* [[September 18]]\n** The Japanese military stage the [[Mukden Incident]], as a pretext for the [[Japanese invasion of Manchuria]].\n** [[Geli Raubal]] commits suicide, in her uncle [[Adolf Hitler]]'s apartment.\n* [[September 20]] \u2013 With a gun literally pointed to his head, the Chinese commander of [[Jilin|Kirin]] province announces the annexation of that territory to Japan.\n* [[September 22]] \u2013 The United Kingdom abandons the [[gold standard]].\n\n===October===\n{{Main|October 1931}}\n* [[October]] \u2013 The [[Caltech]] Department of Physics faculty and graduate students meet with [[Albert Einstein]] as a guest.\n* [[October 4]] \u2013 ''[[Dick Tracy]]'', the comic strip detective character created by cartoonist [[Chester Gould]], makes his debut appearance in the ''[[Detroit Mirror]]'' newspaper.\n* [[October 5]] \u2013 American aviators [[Clyde Edward Pangborn]] and Hugh Herndon, Jr., complete the first [[non-stop flight]] across the Pacific Ocean, from [[Misawa, Aomori|Misawa, Japan]], to [[East Wenatchee, Washington]], in 41\u00bd hours.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pangborn-Herndon Memorial Site|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr//travel/aviation/pan.htm|work=Aviation: From Sand Dunes To Sonic Booms|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref>\n* [[October 11]] \u2013 A rally in Bad Harzburg, Germany leads to the [[Harzburg Front]] being founded, uniting the NSDAP, the DNVP, the ''Stahlhelm'' and various other right-wing factions. \n* [[October 17]]\n** American gangster [[Al Capone]] is sentenced to 11 years in prison for tax evasion in Chicago.\n** [[Leeds Bradford International Airport]] is opened as Leeds and Bradford Municipal Aerodrome, in England.\n* [[October 24]] \u2013 The [[George Washington Bridge]] across the [[Hudson River]] in the United States is dedicated; it opens to traffic the following day. At {{convert|3500|ft|m}}, it nearly doubles the previous record for the [[List of longest suspension bridge spans|longest main span in the world]].\n* [[October 27]] \u2013 The [[1931 United Kingdom general election|United Kingdom general election]] results in the victory of the [[National Government (United Kingdom)|National Government]], and the defeat of [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], in the country's greatest ever electoral landslide.\n\n===November===\n{{Main|November 1931}}\n* [[November 7]] \n** The [[Chinese Soviet Republic]] is proclaimed by [[Mao Zedong]].\n** Red China News Agency (a predecessor of the [[Xinhua News Agency]]) is officially founded, and news wire service start in [[Ruijin]], [[Jiangxi Province]], [[China]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}     \n* [[November 8]]\n** French police launch a large-scale raid against [[Corsica]]n bandits.\n** The [[Panama Canal]] is closed for a couple of weeks, due to damage caused by earthquakes.\n* [[November 21]] \u2013 The infamous Red-and-White Party, given by [[Arthur Jeffress]] in [[Maud Allan]]'s [[Regent's Park]] townhouse in London, marks the end of the \"[[Bright young things]]\" subculture in [[United Kingdom|Britain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elvirabarney.wordpress.com/2011/10/26/the-red-and-white-party/|title=The Red and White Party|work=Cocktails With Elvira|date=2011-10-26|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref>\n* [[November 25]]\n** [[Ali Fethi Okyar]] forms a new government in Turkey (third government).\n** [[James Whale]]'s film of ''[[Frankenstein (1931 film)|Frankenstein]]'' is released in New York City.\n* [[November 26]] \u2013 Heavy hydrogen, later named [[deuterium]], is discovered by American chemist [[Harold Urey]].\n\n===December===\n{{Main|December 1931}}\n* [[December 5]] \u2013 The original [[Cathedral of Christ the Saviour]] in [[Moscow]] ([[1883]]) is dynamited, by order of [[Joseph Stalin]].\n* [[December 8]] \u2013 [[Carl Friedrich Goerdeler]] is appointed Reich Price Commissioner, in Germany to enforce the deflationary policies of the Br\u00fcning government.\n* [[December 9]] \u2013 The Spanish [[Constituent Cortes]] approves the [[Spanish Constitution of 1931]], effectively establishing the [[Second Spanish Republic]].\n* [[December 10]]\n** [[Jane Addams]] becomes the first American woman to be awarded the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n** [[Niceto Alcal\u00e1-Zamora]] is elected president of the Spanish Republic.\n* [[December 11]] \u2013 The [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] enacts the [[Statute of Westminster 1931|Statute of Westminster]], which establishes a status of legislative equality between the self-governing dominions of the [[Commonwealth of Australia]], [[Canada]], the [[Irish Free State]], [[Dominion of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]], the [[Dominion of New Zealand]] and the [[Union of South Africa]].\n* [[December 13]] \u2013 [[Wakatsuki Reijir\u014d]] resigns as [[Prime Minister of Japan]].\n* [[December 19]] \u2013 The [[United Australia Party|UAP]]/[[National Party of Australia|Country]] [[Coalition (Australia)|Coalition]], led by [[Joseph Lyons]], defeats the Australian [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] [[Scullin Ministry|Government]], led by [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] [[James Scullin]]. Coming in the aftermath of two [[Australian Labor Party split of 1931|splits]] in the Labor Party, the election comes about due to the defeat of the Scullin Government on the floor of the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] \u2013 to date, it is the last federal election where a one-term government was defeated. Lyons will be sworn in [[January 6]]th the following year, but not before disbanding the Coalition, after the UAP wins enough seats to form a government in its own right.\n* [[December 26]] \u2013 [[Phi Iota Alpha]], the oldest surviving [[National Association of Latino Fraternal Organizations|Latino fraternity]], is founded in the United States.\n\n==Births==\n{{BDToC|births}}\n\n===January===\n[[File:Toshiki Kaifu (File B).jpg|thumb|100px|[[Toshiki Kaifu]]]]\n[[File:Robert Duvall 2 by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Robert Duvall]]]]\n[[File:Caterina Valente 1966.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Caterina Valente]]]]\n[[File:James Earl Jones (8516667383).jpg|thumb|100px|[[James Earl Jones]]]]\n<!--[[File:Chun Doo-hwan2.png|thumb|100px|[[Chun Doo-hwan]]]]-->\n[[File:Sam_Cooke_billboard.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Sam Cooke]]]]\n[[File:Accadde al commissariato 16 (cropped).jpg|thumb|100px|[[Lucia Bos\u00e8]]]]\n<!--[[File:14 Ernie Banks Medal of Freedom White House (cropped).jpg|thumb|100px|[[Ernie Banks]]]]-->\n* [[January 1]] \u2013 [[Mohammad Ali Samatar]], 5th Prime Minister of Somalia (d. [[2016]])\n* [[January 2]] \u2013 [[Toshiki Kaifu]], 2-time Prime Minister of Japan\n* [[January 4]]\n** [[Guido Messina]], Italian road and track cyclist (d. [[2020]])\n** [[William Deane]], 22nd Governor-General of Australia\n** [[Cleopa Msuya]], 3rd Prime Minister of Tanzania\n** [[Jos\u00e9 Triana (poet)|Jos\u00e9 Triana]], Cuban poet (d. [[2018]])\n* [[January 5]]\n** [[Alvin Ailey]], American choreographer (d. [[1989]])\n** [[Alfred Brendel]], Austrian pianist\n** [[Robert Duvall]], American actor, director\n* [[January 6]]\n** [[E. L. Doctorow]], American author (d. [[2015]])\n** [[Kaoru Yachigusa]], Japanese actress (d. [[2019]])\n* [[January 8]] \u2013 [[Bill Graham (promoter)|Bill Graham]], German concert promoter (d. [[1991]])\n* [[January 10]] \u2013 [[Nik Abdul Aziz Nik Mat]], Malaysian politician, Muslim cleric (d. [[2015]]) \n* [[January 12]] \u2013 [[Roland Alphonso]], Jamaican musician (d. [[1998]])\n* [[January 13]] \u2013 [[Ian Hendry]], English actor (d. [[1984]])\n* [[January 14]] \u2013 [[Caterina Valente]], French singer and actress\n* [[January 16]]\n** [[Shuhrat Abbosov]], Uzbek actor, film director, screenwriter, and film producer (d. [[2018]])\n** [[Johannes Rau]], [[President of Germany]] (d. [[2006]])\n* [[January 17]] \u2013 [[James Earl Jones]], African-American actor\n* [[January 18]] \u2013 [[Chun Doo-hwan]], [[President of South Korea]]\n* [[January 19]] \u2013 [[Pat Hunt]], New Zealand National Party politician\n* [[January 20]] \n** [[Sawako Ariyoshi]], Japanese writer, novelist (d. [[1984]])\n** [[David Lee (physicist)|David Lee]], American physicist, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physics]]\n* [[January 22]] \u2013 [[Sam Cooke]], African-American singer (d. [[1964]])\n* [[January 24]] \u2013 [[Lars H\u00f6rmander]], Swedish mathematician (d. [[2012]])\n* [[January 25]] \u2013 [[Dean Jones (actor)|Dean Jones]], American actor (d. [[2015]])\n* [[January 26]] \u2013 [[Kaare \u00d8rnung]], Norwegian pianist, music teacher (d. [[2013]])\n* [[January 27]] \u2013 [[Mordecai Richler]], Canadian author (d. [[2001]])\n* [[January 28]] \u2013 [[Lucia Bos\u00e8]], Italian actress (d. [[2020]])\n* [[January 29]] \u2013 [[Ferenc M\u00e1dl]], [[President of Hungary]] (d. [[2011]])\n* [[January 31]] \u2013 [[Ernie Banks]], African-American baseball player (d. [[2015]])\n\n===February===\n[[File:\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0415\u043b\u044c\u0446\u0438\u043d-1.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Boris Yeltsin]]]]\n[[File:Dries_van_Agt,_2011_(cropped).jpg|thumb|100px|[[Dries van Agt]]]]\n[[File:Isabel Martinez de Peron.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Isabel Mart\u00ednez de Per\u00f3n]]]]\n<!--[[File:Rip Torn at the 46th Emmy Awards headcrop.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Rip Torn]]]]-->\n[[File:James Dean in Rebel Without a Cause.jpg|thumb|100px|[[James Dean]]]]\n* [[February 1]] \n** [[Boris Yeltsin]], 1st [[President of Russia]] (d. [[2007]])\n** [[Oswald Oberhuber]], Austrian painter, sculptor, and graphic artist (d. [[2020]])\n* [[February 2]]\n** [[Dries van Agt]], Dutch politician, 46th [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands]]\n** [[Walter Burkert]], German writer (d. [[2015]])\n* [[February 4]] \u2013 [[Isabel Mart\u00ednez de Per\u00f3n]], 41st [[President of Argentina]]\n* [[February 6]]\n** [[Rip Torn]], American actor and comedian (d. [[2019]])\n** [[Mamie Van Doren]], American actress, author\n** [[Ricardo Vidal]], Filipino Roman Catholic prelate, cardinal (d. [[2017]])\n* [[February 8]] \n** [[James Dean]], American actor (d. [[1955]])\n** [[Shadia]], Egyptian actress, singer (d. [[2017]])\n* [[February 9]]\n** [[Thomas Bernhard]], Austrian author (d. [[1989]])\n** [[Josef Masopust]], Czech football player and coach (d. [[2015]])\n* [[February 12]] \u2013 [[Agust\u00edn Garc\u00eda-Gasco Vicente]], Spanish cardinal (d. [[2011]])\n* [[February 14]] \u2013 [[Gerrit Jan Hejin]], Dutch businessman (d. [[1987]])\n* [[February 15]] \u2013 [[Claire Bloom]], English actress\n* [[February 16]] \u2013 [[Ken Takakura]], Japanese actor (d. [[2014]])\n* [[February 18]]\n** [[Johnny Hart]], American cartoonist (d. [[2007]])\n** [[Toni Morrison]], African-American writer, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] (d. [[2019]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Obituary: Toni Morrison |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-27635463 |website=BBC News |accessdate=August 6, 2019 |date=August 6, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[February 24]] \u2013 [[Dominic Chianese]], American actor \n* [[February 28]]\n** [[Gavin MacLeod]], American actor, Mayor of [[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles|Pacific Palisades]]\n** [[Dean Smith]], American basketball player and coach (d. [[2015]])\n\n===March===\n[[File:Lamberto dini pl.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Lamberto Dini]]]]\n[[File:Gorbachev (cropped).png|thumb|100px|[[Mikhail Gorbachev]]]]\n[[File:Le\u00f3n Febres Cordero.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Le\u00f3n Febres Cordero]]]]\n<!--[[File:Rupert Murdoch - Flickr - Eva Rinaldi Celebrity and Live Music Photographer.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Rupert Murdoch]]]]-->\n[[File:William Shatner by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|thumb|100px|[[William Shatner]]]]\n[[File:Leonard Nimoy by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Leonard Nimoy]]]]\n<!--[[File:David Janssen Richard Kimble 1963.JPG|thumb|100px|[[David Janssen]]]]-->\n* [[March 1]] \u2013 [[Lamberto Dini]], Italian politician, economist and 51st [[Prime Minister of Italy]]\n* [[March 2]] \u2013 [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], [[President of the Soviet Union]], recipient of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]]\n* [[March 3]] \u2013 [[John Smith (actor)|John Smith]], American actor (d. [[1995]])\n* [[March 4]]\n** [[William H. Keeler]], American Roman Catholic prelate (d. [[2017]])\n** [[Alice Rivlin]], American economist (d. [[2019]])\n* [[March 5]] \u2013 [[Barry Tuckwell]], Australian horn player (d. [[2020]])\n* [[March 8]] \u2013 [[Neil Postman]], American media theorist and cultural critic (d. [[2003]])\n* [[March 9]] \u2013 [[Le\u00f3n Febres Cordero]], President of Ecuador (d. [[2008]])\n* [[March 10]] \u2013 [[Kovambo Nujoma]], First Lady of Namibia \n* [[March 11]] \n** [[Janosch]], German writer\n** [[Rupert Murdoch]], Australian-born publisher\n* [[March 12]] \u2013 [[Herb Kelleher]], American businessman (d. [[2019]])\n* [[March 14]] \u2013 [[Lisbet Palme]], Swedish child psychologist (d. [[2018]])\n* [[March 15]] \u2013 [[D. J. Fontana]], American drummer (d. [[2018]])\n* [[March 18]] \u2013 [[Vlastimil Bubn\u00edk]], Czech ice hockey and football player (d. [[2015]])\n* [[March 20]]\n** [[James Mollison]], Australian arts administrator (d. [[2020]])\n** [[Hal Linden]], American actor, singer (''[[Barney Miller]]'')\n** [[Karen Steele]], American actress and model (d. [[1988]])\n* [[March 22]]\n** [[Paul G. 